\section*{1. INTRODUCTION}

Haemoglobin is the respiratory protein in the red blood cells of vertebrates. Its physiological functions are to transport oxygen from the lungs to the tissues and to facilitate the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs. In its oxygen binding properties and its interactions with other molecules and ions, haemoglobin exhibits phenomena similar to those of many multi-subunit enzymes in their interactions with substrates and cofactors. The intensive study of its structure and reactions has now reached a stage where a detailed model of its function has been developed. This in turn may contribute to the general understanding of the interactions of enzymes.

The approach taken by this article is outlined in section 1.5 of the Introduction. For those new to the subject, the well-established facts concerning haemoglobin structure and functions are given first.

\subsection*{1.1. The Structure of Haemoglobin}

Mammalian haemoglobin has molecular weight of about 64,500 and comprises four subunits, each having one polypeptide chain and one prosthetic group, the haem. The haem group is a protoporphyrin ring at the centre of which is an iron atom in the ferrous state. In free haem the ferrous iron atom is oxidized to ferric by reaction with oxygen whereas in haemoglobin the iron atom combines reversibly with oxygen and stays in the ferrous state in both the oxygenated and deoxygenated forms. This reversible combination with oxygen is made possible in haemoglobin by the folding of the polypeptide chains around the haem groups to enclose them in hydrophobic pockets. The four polypeptide chains are of similar length. Two identical chains, the $\alpha$-chains, each contain 141 amino acids and two other identical chains, the $\beta$-chains, each contain 146 amino acids. Their amino acid sequences have been determined for many species. The form of the backbone of each chain, together with the configuration of the amino acid side chains, is known as the tertiary structure of the subunit. Most of the amino acid residues in both $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits form parts of helices, in which the amino groups of the peptide backbone are hydrogen bonded to the carboxyl groups in adjacent turns. Each subunit contains eight helical segments separated by corners and short, nonhelical regions. The arrangement of the four subunits in the haemoglobin tetramer is known as the quaternary structure.

The structures of haemoglobin with and without oxygen on the haems have been determined by X-ray analysis in sufficient detail to position many of the atoms except hydrogens to within $0.5 \AA$. The two species that have been studied are human and horse haemoglobin. High resolution studies of the deoxygenated forms of the two species show that differences between their tertiary structures are small and that their quaternary structures are virtually identical. Lower resolution studies of the two oxygenated forms show that they have the same quaternary structure as each other. The quaternary structures of oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin, however, are very different. One view of a low resolution model of the structure of horse oxyhaemoglobin is shown in Fig. 1. The structure has a dyad axis which is preserved in the quaternary structure change so that the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{1}$ pair is identical to the $\alpha_{2} \beta_{2}$ pair in both structures. The overall effect of the quaternary structure change between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin is to leave the $\alpha$-chains in much the same positions relative to each other but to increase the separation of the $\beta$-chains so that the space in the central cavity between them is increased and the haem groups are $6 \AA$ further apart. The interface between the $\alpha_{1}$ and

