\subsection*{1.2. The Equilibrium of Haemoglobin with Oxygen}

Haemoglobin reacts reversibly with oxygen at the four haem groups. It picks up oxygen in the lungs, where the oxygen tension is high, and releases it in the tissues where the oxygen tension is low. In muscle the oxygen is taken up by myoglobin which is a single subunit respiratory protein containing only one haem group.

The fraction of haem groups having oxygen bound as a function of partial pressure of oxygen is shown for haemoglobin in Fig. 2, curve a. Such a curve is known as an oxygen equilibrium curve, and for haemoglobin it has the so-called sigmoid shape. The physiological advantage of the sigmoid oxygen equilibrium curve for haemoglobin is seen when it is compared with the corresponding curve for myoglobin, Fig. 2, curve b.

