The partial pressure of oxygen, $p_{50}$, required to produce $50 \%$ saturation of oxygen binding sites is used as a measure of oxygen affinity, so that high affinity corresponds to a small value of $p_{50}$ and low affinity to a large value of $p_{50}$. Myoglobin has a higher affinity for oxygen than has haemoglobin. As the partial pressure of oxygen is reduced from that corresponding to arterial pressure to that corresponding to venous pressure, the percentage saturation of haemoglobin drops from about $95 \%$ to about $73 \%$. At venous pressure the equilibrium saturation of myoglobin is about $90 \%$ so that it takes up and stores the oxygen that the haemoglobin unloads. If haemoglobin had a curve of the myoglobin type that gave the same fractional saturation as haemoglobin does at venous pressure (Fig. 2, curve c), it would be only $87 \%$ saturated at arterial pressure and could thus deliver only two-thirds as much oxygen to the tissues. A further advantage associated with the actual curve is that its steepness at the pressure corresponding to venous pressure enables the amount of oxygen unloaded to be adjusted sensitively by a drop in venous pressure.

The hyperbolic shape of the myoglobin curve is that expected for the combination of one molecule of myoglobin with one molecule of oxygen. The same shape of curve would be expected for haemoglobin if the four stages of oxygenation took place independently. But the sigmoid shape of the haemoglobin curve shows that, as oxygenation proceeds, combination with further molecules of oxygen is made easier. This phenomenon of co-operative interaction in oxygen binding is known as haem-haem interaction. It cannot be due to direct interaction between the binding sites since the haem groups are far apart in the haemoglobin structure. The interaction arises indirectly from conformational changes induced by the binding of oxygen which are associated with the change in quaternary structure between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin.

\subsection*{1.3. Factors Affecting the Oxygen Equilibrium}

The equilibrium of haemoglobin with oxygen is influenced by the presence of ions and molecules that have different binding constants to oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin. The following are three examples of such effects, known as heterotropic interactions.

Binding of hydrogen ions. Both oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin bind hydrogen ions, but at physiological pH deoxyhaemoglobin has the higher affinity for them. Thus hydrogen ions are taken up when oxyhaemoglobin loses oxygen and are released when deoxy-
haemoglobin binds oxygen. The thermodynamically related effect is that the equilibrium between oxygen and haemoglobin is influenced by the concentration of hydrogen ions in solution, the pH . In the physiological range of pH , the oxygen affinity is decreased by lowering the pH and increased by raising it, but the extent of co-operative interaction is scarcely altered. This interaction between the binding of oxygen and of hydrogen ions is known as the Bohr effect. It is responsible for the efficient loading and unloading of oxygen in the lungs and in the tissues respectively, and for facilitating the transport of carbon dioxide in the blood. Most of the carbon dioxide being expelled from the tissues is transported to the lungs dissolved in the blood as carbonic acid, which dissociates with the formation of hydrogen ions
$$\mathrm{CO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \longrightarrow \mathrm{H}^{+}+\mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$$

In the tissues the concentration of dissolved oxygen is low and that of dissolved carbon dioxide is high. The pH is lowered by the increase in $\mathrm{H}^{+}$accompanying the dissolved carbon dioxide thereby lowering the oxygen affinity of haemoglobin. Thus the amount of oxygen that haemoglobin unloads is increased by the presence of dissolved carbon dioxide. As oxyhaemoglobin unloads oxygen, its affinity for hydrogen ions increases, removing them from solution and enabling more carbon dioxide to dissolve in the blood. In the lungs, where the concentration of dissolved oxygen is high and of dissolved carbon dioxide low, the reverse effects combine to increase the loading of haemoglobin with oxygen and to decrease the solubility of carbon dioxide.

Binding of carbon dioxide. Carbon dioxide binds directly to haemoglobin as well as interacting with it by altering the pH of the solution. Both oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin bind carbon dioxide at specific sites on the protein, but deoxyhaemoglobin has the higher affinity. Thus in a way exactly analogous to the binding of hydrogen ions, carbon dioxide is bound by deoxyhaemoglobin in the tissues and released when deoxyhaemoglobin becomes oxygenated in the lungs. Also by analogy, the oxygen affinity of haemoglobin is decreased by the presence of carbon dioxide. This direct interaction between carbon dioxide and haemoglobin accounts for $10 \%$ of the physiological transport of carbon dioxide.

The effect of salts. Deoxyhaemoglobin has a higher affinity for certain salts than has oxyhaemoglobin. So the oxygen affinity of haemoglobin is decreased by increasing salt concentration. The oxygen equilibrium is influenced particularly by organic phosphates such as 2,3-diphosphoglycerate, which is present in the red blood cells of mammals and inositol hexaphosphate, which is closely related to inositol pentaphosphate present in the red blood cells of birds. Organic phosphates have been shown to play a role in adapting the oxygen affinity of haemoglobin to meet the needs of the tissues.

Changes in amino acid sequences of the polypeptide chains. The equilibrium between haemoglobin and oxygen is also altered by changes in the amino acid sequences of the polypeptide chains. These changes can alter the immediate environment of the haem groups and therefore their oxygen binding properties, or they can alter the tertiary structures of the subunits and the way they associate into the tetramer. Haemoglobins from most mammalian species give similar sigmoid oxygenation curves but they differ in their oxygen affinity, extent of co-operativity and heterotropic interactions. The amino acid sequences of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits have been determined for many species, a study of which shows that a large number of invariant residues, including those in the haem environment and the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ contact, are essential for the normal function of tetrameric haemoglobins.

Many mutant forms of human haemoglobin have been discovered. Most of them are due to the mutation of one amino acid in the molecule and in many cases the site of the mutation and the amino acid replacement have been identified. Some have abnormally high or low oxygen affinity and may lack the normal co-operative and heterotropic interactions and the accompanying changes in quaternary conformation.

The oxygen affinity and the co-operative and heterotropic interactions of haemoglobin are greatly affected by some chemical modifications to the protein, for example if the C -terminal residues of either the $\alpha$-or $\beta$-chain are removed by enzymatic digestion.

Experiments on modified haemoglobins have demonstrated the importance for normal functioning of links between the subunits involving the C-terminal residues. Other chemical modifications both inhibit the change of quaternary structure and destroy co-operative interactions, demonstrating the association between these effects. Methods have been developed for separating the haemoglobin tetramer into isolated $\alpha$ and $\beta$-subunits which can then be treated differently before reassembly into a tetramer. Artificial hybrids of many kinds have been produced, for example hybrids in which only one type of subunit can react with oxygen, the other being permanently in the ferric state. Their study makes an important contribution to the understanding of haemoglobin function.

\subsection*{1.4. The Equilibrium of Haemoglobin with Other Ligands}

Haemoglobin combines reversibly at the haem groups with ligands other than oxygen. The co-operative and heterotropic interactions shown by haemoglobin for binding the ligand carbon monoxide are very similar to those shown with oxygen, except that the affinity of haemoglobin for carbon monoxide is about 200 times its affinity for oxygen. Haemoglobin can also be reversibly oxidized to the ferric state, known as methaemoglobin, in which the ligand is a water molecule. The co-operative interactions for oxidation are less than for oxygenation and also vary with pH . Normally, the liganded forms of haemoglobin, whether the iron is ferrous or ferric, all have the same quaternary structure as oxyhaemoglobin whereas deoxyhaemoglobin with no ligand is unique in its structure.

\subsection*{1.5. Outline of this Article}

Some properties of haemoglobin have an explanation in terms of the structures of fully liganded and unliganded haemoglobin, whereas other properties can be understood only in terms of the structures of the intermediate states. These are unobservable and have to be described by a model. This article discusses first those properties of haemoglobin which have an explanation that is independent of a particular model, and then introduces the currently accepted model for the discussion of other properties. The thermodynamics relating to both types of property are given in section 2 . The structures of fully liganded and unliganded haemoglobin are described in section 3. In sections 4 and 5, the functional properties of normal and abnormal haemoglobins are discussed in terms of the fully liganded and unliganded structures, and evidence relating to the intermediate structures is described. Section 6 outlines the type of model of the intermediate states that this evidence suggests, and section 7 gives a detailed discussion of the functional properties of haemoglobin in terms of this model.

\section*{2. THEORY OF LIGAND BINDING TO HAEMOGLOBIN}

\subsection*{2.1. The Equilibrium Binding of Oxygen to Haemoglobin}

Haemoglobin has four subunits, each having one site at which an oxygen molecule can be bound. The reversible combination with oxygen at these four sites can be represented by the following scheme due to Adair (1925):
$$\mathrm{Hb}+4 \mathrm{O}_{2} \xrightarrow{\mathrm{~A}_{1}} \mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \xrightarrow{\mathrm{~A}_{2}} \mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{2}+2 \mathrm{O}_{2} \xrightarrow{\mathrm{~A}_{3}} \mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{3}+\mathrm{O}_{2} \xrightarrow{\mathrm{~A}_{4}} \mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{4}$$

This representation is thermodynamically exact, even if the four sites are not identical, provided that the system is pure and not dissociating into subunits. Four constants, known as the Adair constants, describe the oxygen equilibrium and these can be expressed in terms of the association constants of the actual steps in a specific model for oxygen binding. The Adair constants are given by
$$A_{1}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)\right]}{,[\mathrm{Hb}] \times p}, \quad A_{2}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{2}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)\right] \times p}, \quad A_{3}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{3}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{2}\right] \times p}, \quad A_{4}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{4}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{3}\right] \times p}$$
where all concentrations are expressed in mole fractions. $p$ in mole fractions is related to the partial pressure of oxygen $\mathrm{pO}_{2}$ by a dimensional factor C such that $p=\mathrm{C} \cdot \mathrm{pO}_{2}$. Experimentally determined Adair constants are usually quoted in $(\mathrm{mm} \mathrm{Hg})^{-1}$ and are related to the constants $A$ by the same dimensional factor. In this article $p$ in algebraic expressions should be understood to be in mole fractions, whereas when discussing experimental results $p$ and $A$ will be in mm Hg .

The Adair constants are the macroscopic association constants for the successive steps in the oxygen binding reaction. They can be represented as the product of two factors, an intrinsic association constant for binding oxygen at each step and a statistical factor that takes into account the number of ways in which a given number of oxygen molecules can be distributed among the four subunits. Let $A_{1}^{\prime}, A_{2}^{\prime}, A_{3}^{\prime}, A_{4}^{\prime}$, denote the intrinsic association constants for the four steps of the reaction. Then
$$A_{1}=4 A_{1}^{\prime}, \quad A_{2}=\frac{3}{2} A_{2}^{\prime}, \quad A_{3}=\frac{2}{3} A_{3}^{\prime}, \quad A_{4}=\frac{1}{4} A_{4}^{\prime} .$$

The oxygen equilibrium curve is the plot of the fractional saturation of oxygen combining sites, $\overline{\mathrm{Y}}$, against the partial pressure of oxygen, $p \mathrm{O}_{2}$. By expressing the relative concentrations of haemoglobin molecules with 0 to 4 molecules of oxygen bound in terms of the Adair constants, the fractional saturation of oxygen binding sites, $\bar{Y}$, can be written
$$\bar{Y}=\frac{\left(A_{1} p+2 A_{1} A_{2} p^{2}+3 A_{1} A_{2} A_{3} p^{3}+4 A_{1} A_{2} A_{3} A_{4} p^{4}\right)}{4\left(1+A_{1} p+A_{1} A_{2} p^{2}+A_{1} A_{2} A_{3} p^{3}+A_{1} A_{2} A_{3} A_{4} p^{4}\right)} .$$

If $Y$ is the average number of bound oxygen molecules per haemoglobin molecule,
$$Y=4 \bar{Y} .$$

Equation (2.3) is the general equation for the oxygen equilibrium curve. Written in terms of the intrinsic association constants
$$\bar{Y}=\frac{\left(A_{1}^{\prime} p+3 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} p^{2}+3 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} p^{3}+A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime} p^{4}\right)}{\left(1+4 A_{1}^{\prime} p+6 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} p^{2}+4 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} p^{3}+A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime} p^{4}\right)} .$$

If the intrinsic association constants are all equal to $A^{\prime}$, eq. (2.5) reduces to
$$\bar{Y}=\frac{A^{\prime} p}{1+A^{\prime} p} .$$

This is the equation for the hyperbolic oxygen equilibrium curve (Fig. 2b and c) which is obtained when there is only one binding site for oxygen, as in myoglobin, as well as when the four Adair constants are equal. From eq. (2.6) it can be seen that for very small $p$,
$$\bar{Y} \longrightarrow A^{\prime} p$$
and for very large $p$
$$\bar{Y} \longrightarrow 1-\frac{1}{A^{\prime} p} .$$

If the intrinsic association constants are unequal, and if the association constant for the last step in oxygen binding is greater than that for the first step, the oxygen equilibrium curve will be sigmoid, which can be seen as follows. For very small $p$, eq. (2.5) becomes
$$\bar{Y} \longrightarrow A_{1}^{\prime} p,$$
i.e. the equilibrium curve at small $p$ is the same as the hyperbolic curve corresponding to association constant $A_{1}^{\prime}$. For very large $p$
$$\bar{Y} \longrightarrow 1-\frac{1}{A_{4}^{\prime} p},$$
i.e. the equilibrium curve at large $p$ is the same as the hyperbolic curve corresponding to association constant $A_{4}^{\prime}$. If $A_{4}^{\prime}$ is greater than $A_{1}^{\prime}$, the equilibrium curve must have a sigmoid shape.

The oxygen equilibrium curve for normal haemoglobin does have this sigmoid shape
(Fig. 2a) showing that the last molecule of oxygen combines more easily with oxygen than does the first. The reactivities of the oxygen binding sites must therefore be influenced by the presence of oxygen already combined at the other binding sites, in other words there is co-operative interaction between the binding sites.

The oxygen equilibrium curves of isolated $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains are hyperbolic and are similar to that of myoglobin (Fig. 2b). Isolated $\alpha$-chains are monomeric, whilst $\beta$-chains assemble into a $\beta_{4}$-tetramer which has no interaction between binding sites (Bucci et al., 1965; Tyuma et al., 1966; Geraci et al., 1969). The values of the association constants for oxygen binding to both $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains are similar to that of the last oxygen molecule binding to haemoglobin.

\subsection*{2.2. The Free Energy of Ligand Binding and the Median Ligand Activity}

The standard free energy changes on binding a ligand to haemoglobin at each of the four steps are given by
$$-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{1}^{\prime}, \quad-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{2}^{\prime}, \quad-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{3}^{\prime}, \quad-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{4}^{\prime} .$$

The average free energy of ligand binding over the four successive steps is
$$F_{\mathrm{av}}=-\frac{1}{4} \mathrm{RT} \ln A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime} \text { from (2.7) }$$
where by eqs. (2.1) and (2.2) the product of the intrinsic association constants is
$$A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{4}\right]}{[\mathrm{Hb}] \times p^{4}} .$$

The median ligand activity, $p_{m}$, is defined as the value of $p$ at which the concentration of unliganded and fully liganded molecules are equal,
i.e.
$$\frac{1}{p_{m}^{4}}=A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime}$$

Therefore the average free energy of ligand binding can be written
$$F_{\mathrm{av}}=\mathrm{RT} \ln p_{m}=-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{m}$$
where $A_{m}=1 / p_{m}$.
The concept of median ligand activity was introduced by Wyman $(1964,1967)$ and is a very useful and fundamental parameter of the oxygen equilibrium curve. The median ligand activity for haemoglobin is given by eq. (2.8). For the isolated $\alpha$-and $\beta$-subunits it can be seen that
$$p_{m}=\frac{1}{A^{\prime}}$$

\subsection*{2.3. The Parameters Used to Describe Experimental Oxygen Equilibrium Curves}

Figure 3a shows the oxygen equilibrium curve $\bar{Y}$ against $p \mathrm{O}_{2}$ obtained for a particular set of conditions over as great a range of fractional saturation as is possible experimentally (Tyuma et al., 1973a). In principle the four Adair constants can be determined from a complete equilibrium curve and these give the free energies of ligand binding at the four successive steps, and the value of $p_{m}$. In many cases the equilibrium curve has not been measured over the entire range of fractional saturation. A useful way to present the experimental data is the Hill plot, $\log (\bar{Y} /(1-\bar{Y}))$ against $\log p \mathrm{O}_{2}$. Figure 3b shows the Hill plot of the equilibrium curve in Fig. 3a.

From eq. (2.5),
$$\frac{\bar{Y}}{1-\bar{Y}}=\frac{A_{1}^{\prime} p+3 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} p^{2}+3 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} p^{3}+A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime} p^{4}}{1+3 A_{1}^{\prime} p+3 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} p^{2}+A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} p^{3}} .$$

For very low partial pressures of oxygen,
$$\frac{\bar{Y}}{1-\bar{Y}} \longrightarrow A_{1}^{\prime} p \quad \text { and } \quad \log \frac{\bar{Y}}{1-\bar{Y}} \longrightarrow \log A_{1}^{\prime}+\log p .$$

