$$\frac{\bar{Y}}{1-\bar{Y}} \longrightarrow A_{4}^{\prime} p \quad \text { and } \quad \log \frac{\bar{Y}}{1-\bar{Y}} \longrightarrow \log A_{4}^{\prime}+\log p .$$

Thus the plot of $\log (\overline{\mathrm{Y}} /(1-\overline{\mathrm{Y}}))$ against $\log p$ tends to a straight line of slope unity at very low and very high partial pressures. The asymptote at very low partial pressures has intercept $-\log A_{1}^{\prime}$ on the $\log p$ axis and the asymptote at very high partial pressures has intercept $-\log A_{4}^{\prime}$. Measurements at very high and very low saturations are needed in order to determine these intercepts. If such data are available $A_{1}^{\prime}$ and $A_{4}^{\prime}$ can be estimated and four Adair constants fitted to the complete saturation curve. The Adair constants of the equilibrium curve and Hill plot in Fig. 3 are given in the figure caption.

The difference between the free energies of binding the first and the last ligand, $\Delta F_{I}$, is obtainable from the asymptotes of the Hill plot. Wyman (1964) called $\Delta F_{I}$ the free energy of interaction,
$$\Delta F_{i}=-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{1}^{\prime}+\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{4}^{\prime} .$$

For the data in Fig. 3, this free energy difference is 3.4 kcal per mole haem (Tyuma et al., 1973a).

When the data are not sufficiently extensive, only the steep part of the Hill plot in the middle of the range of saturation can be plotted. Two parameters only, $p_{50}$ and $n$, are then used to characterize the plot.
$p_{50}$ is the value of $p$ required to give $50 \%$ saturation. The expression for $p_{50}$ in terms of the Adair constants is obtained by putting $\overline{\mathrm{Y}}=1-\overline{\mathrm{Y}}$ in eq. (2.11) and is
$$1+2 A_{1}^{\prime} p_{50}=2 A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} p_{50}^{3}+A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime} p_{50}^{4} .$$

In the case when all the Adair constants are equal, $p_{50}$ has a simple value,
$$p_{50}=\frac{1}{A^{\prime}}=p_{m} \quad \text { from }(2.8)$$

Hill's constant, $n$, is the slope of the Hill plot at $50 \%$ saturation and is a useful measure of the extent of interaction between the binding sites. When there is no interaction, $n=1$. If the four oxygen molecules were to combine with haemoglobin in
one step, corresponding to the maximum possible cooperativity, $n=4$. Analytically
$$n=\left(\frac{d \log \frac{\bar{Y}}{1-\bar{Y}}}{d \log p}\right)_{p_{50}}$$
and is a complicated function of $p_{50}$ and the Adair constants. The value of $n$ in the Hill plot for haemoglobin in Fig. 3b is 3.0. The Hill plots for oxygen binding to free $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains are straight lines of slope unity, near the upper asymptote in Fig. 3b. Free subunits have higher oxygen affinity, i.e. lower values of $p_{50}$, than that of the haemoglobin tetramer.

