\subsection*{2.4. The Association of Co-operative Effects with Changes in Stability}

As shown earlier, the sigmoid oxygen equilibrium curve is the result of the greater values of the intrinsic association constants for oxygen in the later stages of the
reaction. The co-operative interaction between binding sites which is the cause of this effect has become known as haem-haem interaction or homotropic interaction. Its relationship to the observed conformation changes induced in the protein as oxygen molecules bind was first discussed by Wyman and Allen (1951). Further studies of the conformation changes associated with ligation have confirmed their central role in the functional properties of haemoglobin. The following representation of the binding of oxygen to haemoglobin, based on the treatment of Wyman (1964) and Noble (1969), emphasizes the relationship betwen the stability of different conformations and the Adair constants of the equilibrium curve.

The haemoglobin molecule is produced by the association of four subunits, $2 \alpha$ and $2 \beta$ into a tetramer. For the initial purposes of this discussion the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits can be regarded as equivalent, each with median ligand activity $p_{s}=1 / A_{s}$. Consider the combination of four deoxy subunits to form deoxyhaemoglobin,
$$4 s \stackrel{\kappa s_{0}}{\longleftrightarrow} \mathrm{Hb} \text { where } K S_{0}=\frac{[\mathrm{Hb}]}{[s]^{4}} .$$
$K S_{0}$ is the overall association constant of four subunits into the tetramer, so that the free energy of association is $\mathrm{RT} \ln \mathrm{KS}_{0}$. The free energy change can be written in terms of one association constant, even though there are many steps in the association. This is analogous to RT $\ln \left(p_{m}^{4}\right)$ being the total free energy change in binding four oxygen molecules to haemoglobin in spite of there being many steps with different microscopic association constants. If the association of subunits to tetramer depends on the state of ligation of the subunits, then $K S_{0}, K S_{1}, \ldots, K S_{4}$ will all be different, e.g.
$$\begin{gathered}
3 s+s \mathrm{O}_{2} \stackrel{K s_{1}}{\longrightarrow} \mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{1}, \\
4 s \mathrm{O}_{2} \stackrel{K s_{4}}{\longrightarrow} \mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{4} .
\end{gathered}$$

In practice the tetramer is very little dissociated into subunits, but the values of these association constants at different stages of ligation give a useful way of expressing the relative stability of the tetramers and free subunits.

The relation between $p_{m}$ for the tetramer and $p_{s}$ for the free subunit. The result of the association of the subunits into a tetramer is to lower the overall affinity for oxygen relative to the affinity of free subunits. The standard free energy change on binding a ligand to a free subunit is $-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{s}$, whereas the average for binding a ligand to a subunit in the tetramer is $-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{m}$. The free energy changes associated with ligand binding to haemoglobin compared to ligand binding to four free subunits are illustrated in Fig. 4. The diagram on the left, (a), indicates that when no ligands are bound to the deoxy tetramer it is more stable than four free deoxy subunits by $\mathrm{RT}_{\mathrm{in}} K S_{\mathrm{o}}$. When four ligands are bound, oxyhaemoglobin is more stable than four free oxy subunits by $\mathrm{RT} \ln \mathrm{KS}_{4}$. Thus from Fig. 4a
$$\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{RT} \ln K S_{0}+4 \mathrm{RT} \ln A_{m}=\mathrm{RT} \ln K S_{4}+4 \mathrm{RT} \ln A_{s}, \\
\ln A_{m}=\ln A_{s}+\frac{1}{4} \ln \frac{K S_{4}}{K S_{0}}
\end{gathered}$$
or
$$\ln p_{m}=\ln p_{s}+\frac{1}{4} \ln \frac{K S_{0}}{K S_{4}} .$$

Thus the difference between $p_{m}$ and $p_{s}$ is related to the association constants of oxy and deoxy subunits into the tetramer. The structural features associated with this stability difference may be identifiable. For example, $\mathrm{RT} \ln \boldsymbol{K} \boldsymbol{S}_{\mathbf{0}}$, the free energy change accompanying assembly of deoxy subunits into a tetramer is expected to be related both to any change in tertiary structure between free deoxy subunits and those in a tetramer and to the free energy changes associated with the formation of intersubunit contacts rather than contacts with the solvent. Similarly $\mathbf{R T} \ln \mathbf{K S}_{4}$ will be related to the corresponding structural features for oxy subunits and oxyhaemoglobin. So from a knowledge of the three-dimensional structures of oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin and of

