Co-operativity. From Fig. 4a, looking in turn at the free energy after each stage of ligation of the tetramer, the following equations for the Adair constants can be written down:
$$\begin{array}{ll}
\ln A_{1}^{\prime}=\ln A_{5}+\ln K S_{1}-\ln K S_{0} ; & A_{1}^{\prime}=A_{5}\left(K S_{1} / K S_{0}\right), \\
\ln A_{2}^{\prime}=\ln A_{5}+\ln K S_{2}-\ln K S_{1} ; & A_{2}^{\prime}=A_{3}\left(K S_{2} / K S_{1}\right), \\
\ln A_{3}^{\prime}=\ln A_{3}+\ln K S_{3}-\ln K S_{2} ; & A_{3}^{\prime}=A_{3}\left(K S_{3} / K S_{2}\right), \\
\ln A_{4}^{\prime}=\ln A_{3}+\ln K S_{4}-\ln K S_{3} ; & A_{4}^{\prime}=A_{3}\left(K S_{4} / K S_{3}\right) .
\end{array}$$

The individual Adair constants are therefore related to the stability of the partially liganded states. If all the $K S_{i}$ are equal, the Adair constants will all be the same, there will be no co-operativity and the affinity of the tetramer will be the same as that of the subunit. If the ratios of successive $K S_{i}$ 's are all equal, i.e. $K S_{1} / K S_{0}=K S_{2} / K S_{1}$, etc., then again the Adair constants will all be the same, there will be no co-operativity but the association constant of the tetramer for oxygen will be $A_{3} K S_{1} / K S_{0}$. One of these situations must apply to the $\beta_{4}$-tetramer and any abnormal haemoglobin that shows no co-operativity. There will be interaction in oxygen binding, either co-operative or anti-cooperative, if the ratios of successive subunit to tetramer association constants differ.

The difference in free energy of binding between the first and last step, $\Delta F_{I}$ will be positive provided $A_{4}^{\prime}>A_{1}^{\prime}$, i.e. provided
$$\frac{K S_{4}}{K S_{3}}>\frac{K S_{1}}{K S_{0}} .$$

Thus $\Delta F_{I}$ is positive if the change in stability produced by binding the first ligand is greater than the change in stability produced by binding the last ligand. It can be seen to be independent of $\mathrm{KS}_{2}$.

The value of $n$, which measures the overall co-operativity, will depend on the changes of stability at each step. A structural explanation of the stability differences that are related to $\Delta F_{I}$ and the value of $n$ requires a knowledge of the structures of the intermediate states, and therefore cannot be understood directly from the results of three-dimensional structure determinations of fully liganded and unliganded haemoglobin. Other properties of haemoglobin provide information on the nature of these intermediate structures. Before discussing differences of conformation in haemoglobin
at different states of ligation, it is interesting to compare the ligand binding properties of haemoglobin to those of free chains.

