$$\ln p_{m x}=\ln p_{m}+\frac{1}{4}\left[\ln \left(1+B_{0} x\right)-\ln \left(1+B_{4} x\right)\right] .$$

Therefore the change in oxygen affinity, $\Delta \ln p_{m}$, is related to the association constants of $X$ to deoxy and fully liganded haemoglobin and is independent of the binding of $X$ to the intermediate structures provided $x$ is buffered or effectively constant.

By analogy with eqs. (2.16) the Adair constants are given by
$$\begin{array}{ll}
\ln A_{1 x}^{\prime}=\ln A_{3}+\ln K S_{1}\left(1+B_{1} x\right)-\ln K S_{0}\left(1+B_{0} x\right), \\
\ln A_{1 x}^{\prime}=\ln A_{1}^{\prime}+\left[\ln \left(1+B_{1} x\right)-\ln \left(1+B_{0} x\right)\right] ; & A_{1 x}^{\prime}=A_{1}^{\prime} \frac{\left(1+B_{1} x\right)}{\left(1+B_{0} x\right)}, \\
\ln A_{2 x}^{\prime}=\cdots, & A_{2 x}^{\prime}=A_{2}^{\prime} \frac{\left(1+B_{2} x\right)}{\left(1+B_{1} x\right)}, \\
\ln A_{3 x}^{\prime}=\cdots, & A_{3 x}^{\prime}=A_{3}^{\prime} \frac{\left(1+B_{3} x\right)}{\left(1+B_{2} x\right)}, \\
\ln A_{4 x}^{\prime}=\ln A_{4}^{\prime}+\left[\ln \left(1+B_{4} x\right)-\ln \left(1+B_{3} x\right)\right] ; & A_{4 x}^{\prime}=A_{4}^{\prime} \frac{\left(1+B_{4} x\right)}{\left(1+B_{3} x\right)} .
\end{array}$$

This shows that the differences in co-operativity, i.e. differences in the ratios of the Adair constants, are related to the binding constants of $X$ to the intermediate structures.

The number of molecules, $\Delta X_{1}$, of bound $X$ released per mole haemoglobin in the first ligation step is
$$\begin{aligned}
\Delta X_{1} & =\frac{[H b X]}{[H b]+[H b X]}-\frac{\left[H b\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right) X\right]}{\left[H b\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)\right]+\left[H b\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right) X\right]}, \\
\Delta X_{1} & =\frac{B_{0} x}{1+B_{0} x}-\frac{B_{4} x}{1+B_{4} x} \\
& =-\frac{d \ln A_{1 x}^{\prime}}{d \ln x}
\end{aligned}$$
as can be shown by differentiating (2.20). Similarly for successive ligation steps,
$$\Delta X_{i}=-\frac{d \ln A_{i x}^{\prime}}{d \ln x} .$$

Thus some $X$ is released at each stage in ligand binding if the corresponding Adair constant changes with concentration $x$. Conversely, no $X$ is released at any stage for which the Adair constant is independent of $x$. Also $X$ will be released uniformly with ligation only if all the Adair constants depend on $x$ in the same way.

The total number of moles of bound $X$ released per mole haemoglobin,
$$\begin{aligned}
\Delta X & =\sum_{i=1}^{4} \Delta X_{i} \\
& =4 \frac{d \ln p_{m x}}{d \ln x} \quad \text { since } \quad p_{m x}=\frac{1}{A_{1 x}^{\prime} A_{2 x}^{\prime} A_{3 x}^{\prime} A_{4 x}^{\prime}} \\
\frac{\Delta X}{4} & =\frac{d \ln p_{m x}}{d \ln x}
\end{aligned}$$

This is a linkage relation (Wyman, 1964) for the case when one mole $X$ binds per mole tetramer of haemoglobin, as is the case for the binding of organic phosphates.

The general linkage relations. In general there will be many sites on the protein for binding a ligand $X$ and the sites may interact so that the binding of $X$ is co-operative or anti-cooperative. For example, haemoglobin binds protons at many sites and the general relations that will be derived below will be applicable to this case.

If there are $q$ sites per tetramer for binding $X$ and if the free subunits do not bind $X$, the equilibrium between subunits, deoxy tetramer and $X$ can be represented by
