$$\Delta X_{i}=-\frac{d \log A_{i x}^{\prime}}{d \log x}$$

This is the general expression for release of $X$ at each stage of ligation. $\Delta X$, the total number of molecules of $X$ released on oxygenation per tetramer, is the sum of the $\Delta X_{i}$,
$$\Delta X=-\frac{d \log A_{1 x}^{\prime} A_{2 x}^{\prime} A_{3 x}^{\prime} A_{4 x}^{\prime}}{d \log x} .$$

So by the definition of $p_{m x}$
$$\Delta X=\frac{4 d \log p_{\operatorname{mx}}}{d \log x} .$$

If there are $q$ sites for $X, \Delta \bar{X}$, the change in fractional saturation of the $X$ binding sites on oxygenation is given by
$$\Delta \bar{X}=\frac{4}{q} \frac{d \log p_{m x}}{d \log x} .$$

This general form of linkage equation applies to cases like proton binding when there are many binding sites which may interact with each other. Equations (2.25) and (2.29) show the general relations between $\log p_{m x}$ and the buffered concentration of ligand $X$ in solution. These expressions involve only the binding constants of $X$ to deoxy and fully oxygenated haemoglobin and are therefore independent of the binding of $X$ to intermediate states.

A structural explanation of the effect of protons on the oxygen affinity $p_{m}$ should therefore be possible from a knowledge of the structures of deoxy and fully liganded haemoglobin.

The expression when the $q$ binding sites for $X$ are non-interacting. If there is no interaction between the $q$ binding sites for $X$ on the tetramer, each binding site will have an independent microscopic association constant. Let $Q_{i j}$ denote the binding constant for $X$ to the $j$ th site on haemoglobin when there are $i$ oxygen molecules bound. In this case the binding polynomials $\phi_{i}(x)$ can be factorized and can be written
$$\phi_{1}(x)=\left(1+Q_{11} x\right)\left(1+Q_{12} x\right) \ldots\left(1+Q_{1 q} x\right),$$
where the relationships between the constants $Q_{i j}$ and the constants $B_{i j}$ of the general polynomial can be seen by equating the coefficients of powers of $x$.

The expression for $\log p_{m x}$ then becomes, from (2.25),
$$\log p_{m x}=\log p_{m}+\frac{1}{4} \sum_{j=1}^{q}\left[\log \left(1+Q_{0 j} x\right)-\log \left(1+Q_{4 j} x\right)\right] .$$

The total release of $X$ can be expressed as a summation over the amount of $X$ released independently from each of the $j$ sites,
$$\Delta X=\sum_{j=1}^{q} \Delta X_{j} \quad \text { where } \quad \Delta X_{j}=\frac{d}{d \log x} \log \left(\frac{1+Q_{0 j} x}{1+Q_{4 j} x}\right) .$$

Changes in co-operativity with change in concentration of $X$. As discussed in section 2.4, differences in co-operativity are associated with differences in the relative stabilities of the partially liganded states. When a ligand involved in heterotropic interactions binds to haemoglobin, the Adair constants are multiplied by terms involving the concentration of the ligand (eq. (2.26)). If all the Adair constants are multiplied by the same factor, their ratios and therefore the co-operativity will remain the same, i.e. the shape of the oxygen equilibrium curve will be unaltered. In this case the equilibrium curve will just be shifted parallel to the $\log p$ axis. If the Adair constants are multiplied by different factors, the co-operativity and the shape of the equilibrium curve must change. An understanding of these changes in co-operativity will require an understanding of the structure of the partially oxygenated states.

The condition for linearity of release of $X$ with oxygen binding.
$$\Delta X_{i}=-\frac{d \log A_{i x}^{\prime}}{d \log x} \quad \text { from eq.(2.27). }$$

Release of $X$ is the same at all stages of oxygen binding if the Adair constants all depend on the concentration of $X$ in the same way, i.e. they have the same concentration dependent term as a multiplier. As just discussed above, this is the condition for invariance of shape of the equilibrium curves as the concentration of $X$ varies. Linearity of release of $X$ and invariance of shape of the equilibrium curves with change in concentration of $X$ are therefore thermodynamic consequences of each other, or in Wyman's terminology they are linked.

One particularly simple example in which release of $X$ is exactly linear with oxygenation is the case when each subunit within the tetramer releases ligand only due to changes in tertiary structure depending on its own state of oxygenation, independently of the state of oxygenation of the other subunits. Then each Adair constant has a multiplying term
$$\left(\frac{1+Q_{s 1} x}{1+Q_{s 0} x}\right)$$
where $Q_{s 0}$ is the binding constant of $X$ to the deoxy subunit and $Q_{s 1}$ the binding constant to the oxy subunit. The release of $X$ at each stage of oxygenation is
$$\Delta X_{i}=\frac{d}{d \log x} \log \left(\frac{1+Q_{s 1} x}{1+Q_{s 0} x}\right)=\frac{Q_{s 0} x}{1+Q_{s 0} x}-\frac{Q_{s 1} x}{1+Q_{s 1} x}$$
and the total release is $4 \Delta X_{i}$.
The discussion in section 2.6 has emphasized that from observations of the three-dimensional structures of fully liganded and unliganded haemoglobin determined by X-ray analysis, an understanding of changes in oxygen affinity due to abnormalities in the protein or due to the presence of ligands producing heterotropic interactions may be found. Changes in co-operativity, however, require an understanding of intermediate states that cannot be observed by X-ray techniques. It will be useful to consider these two aspects of altered function in two stages, those aspects that might be explained in terms of the known structures and those that will require some model of the intermediate structures for their interpretation. The following section will describe the structures of fully liganded and unliganded haemoglobin. The understanding they provide of some aspects of heterotropic interaction and the properties of abnormal haemoglobins will be discussed in sections 4 and 5.

\section*{3. THE STRUCTURE OF HAEMOGLOBIN}

The three-dimensional structure of haemoglobin has been studied by the methods of X-ray crystallography. From low resolution studies, the haemoglobin molecule was shown to comprise two pairs of identical subunits, the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains (Cullis et al., 1962). The structure of each subunit is similar to that of the monomeric respiratory protein myoglobin (Kendrew et al., 1961). The four subunits are arranged tetrahedrally and the structure is such that the four haem groups, the binding sites for oxygen, are far apart, each in a separate pocket on the surface of the molecule. The arrangement of the four subunits in the haemoglobin tetramer is different in deoxygenated and liganded haemoglobin (Muirhead and Perutz, 1963), explaining Haurowitz's observation (1938) that crystals of deoxyhaemoglobin dissolve on exposure to air and that oxyhaemoglobin crystals with a different morphology precipitate from the solution. Electron density maps have now been made at high resolution $(\sim 2.8 \AA)$ for horse methaemoglobin (i.e. haemoglobin with the iron atoms in the ferric state with water molecules as haem ligands) and for horse and human deoxyhaemoglobin (Perutz et al., 1968a, 1968b; Bolton and Perutz, 1970; Muirhead and Greer, 1970; Arnone et al., 1975). With the aid
of the amino acid sequences of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-polypeptide chains, which have been determined for both horse and human haemoglobin (see Dayhoff, 1973) atomic models of the structures have been built from the electron density maps. The accuracy of the latest models is such that from the better determined regions of the maps, for example the polypeptide backbone in helical regions and the internal side chains, the atoms, except for hydrogens, can be positioned to within $0.5 \AA$. The surface side chains and some parts of the structure that are ill defined in the maps are positioned less well (McLachlan and Fermi, 1975). The following sections will discuss briefly those aspects of the structures of deoxy and liganded haemoglobin that are important in the present understanding of haemoglobin function.

