\subsection*{3.2. The Structure of Subunits}

Although there are differences in amino acid sequence between the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains of haemoglobin, erythrocruorin and myoglobin, the polypeptide chains fold around the haem groups to give a very similar tertiary structure in each case, whether the chains are liganded or not. The haem group is situated in a hydrophobic pocket formed by the polypeptide chain. Comparison of the sequences of different mammalian species show that all but one of the amino acids in contact with the $\alpha$-haem group are invariant and all but two in contact with the $\beta$-haem group (Perutz et al., 1968b).

Figure 6 illustrates the tertiary structure of a subunit and shows the conventional labelling of the $\alpha$-helical segments of the structure. The $\alpha$-chains of haemoglobin contain 141 residues each, compared to 153 in myoglobin. Six of the missing residues are from the D-helix which is absent in the $\alpha$-chain, and the other six are at the carboxyl end of the chain (Perutz et al., 1968b). The $\beta$-chains contain 146 residues each and compared to myoglobin they contain one extra residue in the NA segment, two fewer in the AB corner and six fewer at the C terminus.

The structure of free subunits. Since the isolated $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits of haemoglobin have not been studied by X-ray analysis, the structures of sperm-whale myoglobin (Kendrew et al., 1961) and the insect haemoglobin erythrocruorin (Huber et al., 1970), which is also monomeric, can be used to discuss the structural features of single subunits, and the changes in structure seen when the ligand at the haem group changes. Erythrocruorin has been studied in the met, deoxy and carbonmonoxy forms at $2.5 \AA$ resolution, whilst myoglobin has been studied in the met form to $2.0 \AA$ resolution and in the azide, met and deoxy forms.

In meterythrocruorin, the iron atom lies $0.3 \AA$ from the plane defined by the centres of the four pyrrole rings. As the atoms of the porphyrin are not resolved, the puckering of the haem group was assumed to be the same as that in the ferric porphyrin complex studied by Hoard et al. (1965). The iron atom is out of the plane towards the haem-linked histidine, whilst the water molecule that is the haem ligand in aquomethaemoglobin is on the other side of the haem group, $1.9 \AA$ from the iron atom. In sperm-whale myoglobin, the iron atom lies $0.42 \AA$ out of the mean plane of the porphyrin ring (Takano, 1975).

