Deoxyhaemoglobin does not dissociate detectably at pH 7.0 even in strong salt solution (Kellett and Gutfreund, 1970; Kellett, 1971b). At very high pH , deoxyhaemoglobin can be made to dissociate into an ( $\alpha_{1} \beta_{1}$ ) dimer which has an absorption spectrum like that of free chains and fast carbon monoxide binding kinetics (Anderson et al., 1971). Kellett (1971b) also showed that the deoxy dimer formed in 2 m NaI possesses properties similar to isolated chains. Deoxyhaemoglobin digested with carboxypeptidase B which removes the C-terminal arginines $141 \alpha$ can be made to form dimers in strong salt ( $1 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{MgCl}_{2}$ ) and these deoxy dimers also have absorption spectra like free chains and are non-cooperative in ligand binding (Hewitt et al., 1972). The measured value of $p_{50}$ for oxygen binding to des(Arg) dimers is 0.4 mm Hg , very similar to the value for free chains shown in Table 1. Thus the free $\alpha \beta$ dimer has been shown to be non-cooperative and to have ligand binding properties and absorption spectra like those of free chains. The tetramer is the co-operative unit in haemoglobin as was suggested from kinetic evidence by Gibson and Parkhurst (1968). Structural reasons why the tetramer is essential for co-operativity were first discussed by Perutz et al. (1968b) and recent theories of haemoglobin function are based on the tetramer as the functional unit.

The affinities of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in the dimer. The macromolecule haptoglobin has been shown to bind only to the $\alpha \beta$ dimer (Nagel and Gibson, 1971). It binds much more strongly to liganded haemoglobin, which forms dimers in a significant amount, than to deoxyhaemoglobin which does not. Haptoglobin binding to deoxyhaemoglobin is too small to be detected in the presence of phosphates but can just be detected for haemoglobin stripped of phosphates (Nagel and Gibson, 1972). As expected from the linkage between dissociation and oxygen affinity (section 2.5) the haemoglobin-haptoglobin complex has very much higher affinity than has normal haemoglobin. In addition homo- and heterotropic interactions are absent in the complex with one mole haptoglobin per mole dimer. The absorption spectrum from the haem groups, the rate of carbon monoxide binding and the oxygen equilibrium properties are like those of free chains with $n=1$ and $p_{s o}=0.45 \mathrm{~mm} \mathrm{Hg}$ at $20^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ (Nagel et al., 1965; Chiancone et al., 1973). Since $n=1$, the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in the dimer cannot be very different in regards their oxygen affinities and are therefore like the free subunits. The oxidation of haemoglobin bound to haptoglobin also shows the similarity in properties of free chains and the $\alpha \beta$ dimer. In this case there is slight negative co-operativity, consistent with the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in the dimer having the different oxidationreduction potentials characteristic of the free subunits (Brunori et al., 1968a). At pH 7.0 in 0.1 m phosphate, the oxidation-reduction potentials of the two components in the dimer are $E_{1}=0.106$ and $E_{2}=0.050$, whereas at pH 9.15 they are 0.044 and 0.022 . These oxidation-reduction potentials, multiplied by $(F / 2.3 \mathrm{RT})=16.65$, are equivalent to log $p_{50}$ values (see section 2.5) and show an equivalent difference in affinity between the
chains in the dimer of a factor 8.5 at pH 7.0 and about 2.5 at pH 9.0 . These relative affinities of the chains in the dimer can be compared to those for the isolated chains determined by Banerjee and Cassoly (1969a), who found the $\beta$-chains to be less easily oxidized than the $\alpha$-chains by a factor of about 10 at pH 7.0 , but equally easily oxidized at pH 8.0 . The two sets of results are sufficiently consistent to indicate that the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chain properties are not altered by association into the dimer.

Estimation of tetramer-dimer dissociation constant for deoxyhaemoglobin. The liganded structure is expected to dissociate to subunits more easily than the deoxy structure from the considerations discussed in section 2.5. As it has now been shown both that the free dimer is non-cooperative and has chain-like ligand binding properties, and that the dissociation of dimer to monomer does not take place in moderate ionic strength, the argument of section 2.5 can be used to estimate the dissociation constant of deoxyhaemoglobin to dimers. Let $p_{d}$ denote the median ligand activity of the dimer, and $p_{m}$, as before, that of the tetramer. The association constants of subunits to tetramers are related to those of dimers to tetramers by
$$K S_{0}=\frac{1}{K_{T, D(\text { deoxy })}\left(K_{D, M}\right)^{2}}$$
and
$$K S_{4}=\frac{1}{K_{T, D(\mathrm{oxy})}\left(K_{D, M}\right)^{2}}$$
where $\boldsymbol{K}_{\mathbf{T}, \boldsymbol{D}}$ denotes the tetramer-dimer dissociation constant and $\boldsymbol{K}_{D, M}$ the dimer-monomer dissociation constant which is independent of the state of oxygenation. Equation (2.15) becomes
$$\ln p_{m}=\ln p_{d}+\frac{1}{4} \ln \frac{K_{T, D(\mathrm{oxy})}}{K_{T, D(\mathrm{deoxy})}} .$$

Using the data previously taken as an example, that of Tyuma et al. (1973a) where log $p_{m}=0.737$ in 0.1 m NaCl at pH 7.4 , and taking $\log p_{d}=-0.4$ similar to the free chains value
$$\frac{K_{T, D(\text { oxy })}}{K_{T, D(\text { deoxy })}}=3.5 \times 10^{4} .$$

Taking the value of $K_{T, D(\text { oxy })}$ from Table 9, $K_{T, D(\text { deoxy })}$ is estimated to be $10^{-10} \mathrm{M}$ in 0.1 M NaCl at pH 7.4. Thomas and Edelstein (1972) have estimated $K_{T, D(\text { deoxy })}$ to be $4 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~m}$ by the same method, approximating the median ligand activity by the value of $p_{50}$. The value of $K_{T, D(d e o x y)}$ depends on pH and organic phosphate concentration since $p_{m}$ depends on these as discussed in section 2.6.2.

\section*{4. THE INTERACTION WITH PROTONS AND ORGANIC PHOSPHATES}

This section will discuss the extent to which the three-dimensional structures of deoxy and fully liganded haemoglobin, described in section 3, account for the differences in their binding constants for protons and organic phosphates, and hence for their altered oxygen affinities ( $p_{m}$ ) in the presence of these ligands. The evidence on the binding of these ligands to partially oxygenated haemoglobin will also be examined in preparation for later discussion of the conformation of the intermediate structures.

Carbon dioxide binding to haemoglobin will not be included in the discussion here although it is another example of heterotropic interaction in haemoglobin. For information on the interaction of haemoglobin with this ligand the reader is referred to the section on this topic in the recent review by Kilmartin and Rossi-Bernardi (1973).

\subsection*{4.1. The Interaction of Haemoglobin with Protons. The Bohr Effect}

As mentioned in the introduction, the Bohr effect is responsible for the influence of dissolved carbon dioxide on the oxygen affinity of haemoglobin. The effect was first noticed by Bohr et al. (1904). The phenomenon that oxygenated blood dissolved less carbon dioxide than deoxygenated blood was noticed later (Christiansen et al., 1914).

Henderson (1920) showed that these effects could be accounted for by an interaction between haemoglobin and hydrogen ions in such a way that deoxyhaemoglobin binds more hydrogen ions at physiological pH than does oxyhaemoglobin.

