The acid Bohr effect is believed to be due to different ionization constants of carboxyl groups in oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin (Antonini et al., 1965c) but it is not known yet which particular groups contribute. Perutz (1970) has suggested that the acid Bohr effect is connected with a further quaternary structure change that takes place at about pH 6.0 .

The residual oxidation Bohr effect has not been interpreted structurally. Its constancy under different conditions, and its presence in myoglobin suggests that it is a direct effect from a local conformational change in the neighbourhood of the haem (Brunori et al., 1969).

\subsection*{4.1.3. The binding of protons to partially oxygenated haemoglobin}

The shape of the equilibrium curves as a function of pH , and the release of protons at successive steps in oxygenation. As discussed in section 2.6, eq. (2.27), the difference in number of protons bound at successive stages of partial oxygenation is related to the dependence of the Adair constants on pH . Writing $x=h$ and $\Delta X_{i}=\Delta H_{i}^{+}$, the release of protons at each stage of ligation is given by
$$\Delta H_{i}^{+}=-\frac{d \log A_{i}^{\prime}}{d \log h}=\frac{d \log A_{i}^{\prime}}{d \mathrm{pH}} .$$

That is, the number of protons released at each stage is related to the variation of shape of the oxygen equilibrium curve with pH . If the shape is invariant with pH , the Bohr effect and co-operativity are independent phenomena, whereas if the shape changes with pH they are interdependent or coupled.

For some time the experimental evidence was believed to support invariance of shape of the equilibrium curves with pH (Antonini et al., 1963) although there was some evidence that the shape varied at very high or very low saturations (see Roughton, 1964). The evidence supporting invariance of shape included the apparent linearity of the fractional release of protons as a function of oxygen saturation, which as seen in section 2.6 is a corollary of shape invariance, and the agreement of the two methods of determining the Bohr effect. Experimentally the Bohr effect is measured either by the release of bound hydrogen ions on oxygenation, $\Delta H^{+}$, or by the change in $\log p_{50}$ with pH. Since
$$\frac{\Delta H^{+}}{4}=-\frac{d \log p_{m}}{d \mathrm{pH}} \quad \text { from (4.2) }$$
the two experimental measures,
$$\frac{\Delta H^{+}}{4} \quad \text { and } \quad \frac{-d \log p_{50}}{d \mathrm{pH}}$$
will give exactly the same results only if $p_{m}=p_{50}$ at all pH , i.e. the Hill plots are always symmetrical, or if the Hill plots are exactly the same shape at all pH . The evidence was interpreted as showing that the release of protons is equivalent for the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains and is entirely associated with tertiary structure changes induced by ligation within each subunit, quite independently of the state of ligation of other subunits.

Later results have shown that the slope of the Hill plot varies slightly with pH (Bunn and Guidotti, 1972; Tyuma et al., 1973b; Imai and Yonetani, 1975), and recent comparisons of the two measures of the Bohr effect have revealed a small difference of about 5\% (Siggaard-Anderson et al., 1972). The Adair constants of the oxygen equilibrium curves measured at several pH values by Imai and Yonetani are shown in Table 11, where it can be seen that the successive Adair constants are not all altered by the same factor when the pH is changed. The release of protons at successive steps in oxygenation can be estimated from this data.
