\subsection*{4.2.3. The binding sites for DPG, IHP and salts}

DPG binds to deoxyhaemoglobin with a stoichiometry of one mole per tetramer indicating the probability of a binding site on the dyad axis of the molecule, and it also binds to the $\beta_{4}$ tetramer suggesting a site between the $\beta$-chains (Benesch et al., 1968). DPG has a much smaller effect on the oxygen equilibrium of those haemoglobins which lack the free N -terminal amino group of the $\beta$-chains (Bunn and Briehl, 1970). From model building studies, Perutz (1970) showed that it is possible for DPG to bind between the $N$-terminal amino groups of the $\beta$-chains on the dyad axis of the molecule in the deoxyhaemoglobin structure, but that the space between the $\beta$-chains at the same site is too small in oxyhaemoglobin.

The exact position of DPG in this binding site has now been found by X-ray analysis of the human deoxyhaemoglobin structure with DPG bound (Arnone, 1972). The anionic groups of DPG form salt bridges with seven cationic groups of the $\beta$-chains which include the $\alpha$-amino group of valine $1 \beta$, histidine $2 \beta$ and histidine $143 \beta$ of both chains and lysine $82 \beta$ of one chain (see Fig. 11a). In addition to binding at this site, DPG produces small changes in tertiary structure in the $\beta$-chains including the pulling of the $\alpha$-amino groups together, resulting in a movement of the A helices. This work also revealed that the binding of DPG displaces an inorganic anion from a position between Lys $82 \beta$ and the N-terminus, giving a structural interpretation of the competition between DPG and NaCl binding. Yet further confirmation of the phosphate binding site in deoxyhaemoglobin is provided by the study of the binding of pyridoxal phosphate. This was shown to bind to the N -terminus of the $\beta$-chains (Benesch et al., 1972).

The binding site for DPG in oxyhaemoglobin has not yet been identified. DPG cannot bind in exactly the same site in oxyhaemoglobin as in deoxyhaemoglobin as the space between the $\beta$-chains is narrower and there would not be room for it. It has been shown that pyridoxal phosphate and other pyridoxal derivatives bind to oxyhaemoglobin at the N -terminus of the $\alpha$-chains indicating that this site is a possibility (Benesch et al., 1972, 1973).

IHP has been shown to bind to the same binding site in deoxyhaemoglobin as that for DPG (Arnone and Perutz, 1974) with the six phosphates coordinated to the same basic groups that bind DPG (see Fig. 11b). In addition to these eight basic groups the amino groups of the asparagines $139 \beta$ may form hydrogen bonds with two of the phosphate groups of IHP. IHP produces tertiary structure changes in the $\beta$-chains similar to those produced when DPG is bound. These changes may be associated with the difference in affinity of haemoglobin for its first ligand in the presence and absence of DPG and IHP (see section 4.2.4). The binding site for IHP in oxyhaemoglobin has not yet been

