\subsection*{4.2.6. The effect of organic phosphates on preferential binding of ligands to $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains}

Gray and Gibson (1971a, b) have shown that the presence of IHP decreases the rate constant for uptake of carbon monoxide by haemoglobin, and that it produces a large difference in rate constant between the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains. This difference in rate for $\alpha$ and $\beta$-chains is not observed in haemoglobin stripped of phosphates, and is not very marked in the presence of inorganic phosphate or DPG. Gray and Gibson suggest that the $\beta$-chains take up carbon monoxide faster than $\alpha$-chains, by analogy with the results with n-BIC, which shows heterogeneity in the absence of phosphates which is amplified by the presence of IHP (Olson and Gibson, 1970). This heterogeneity with n-BIC is observed by NMR methods (Lindstrom et al., 1971) and preferential binding to the $\beta$-chains has been shown. NMR studies have also shown that heterogeneity between $\alpha$ and $\beta$-chains for oxygen and carbon monoxide binding is amplified by the presence of organic phosphates (Johnson and Ho, 1974). Carbon monoxide binds equally to $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in stripped haemoglobin, shows a very slight preference for $\alpha$-chains in the presence of DPG, and a greater preference for $\alpha$-chains in the presence of IHP. Oxygen binding shows a slight preference for $\alpha$-chains in stripped haemoglobin, a marked preference in the presence of DPG and a very marked preference in the presence of IHP, the affinity of the $\alpha$-chain then being greater than that for $\beta$-chains by a factor of 10. Gibson (1973a) also finds differences in the kinetic aspects of carbon monoxide and oxygen binding. These results show that the assumption usually made that carbon monoxide and oxygen binding are equivalent except for a scale factor altering the affinity is not correct in detail, although the overall shape of equilibrium curves and kinetic progress curves appears to be the same.

\subsection*{4.2.7. The decrease in co-operativity for oxidation in the presence of IHP}

