Conformation differences at the haem groups between methaemoglobin in the presence and absence of IHP have also been found (Perutz et al., 1974b). There are differences in the electronic absorption spectrum of the haem groups, in the NMR spectra from haem contact residues, and in the paramagnetic susceptibility. Methaemoglobin has a higher susceptibility in the presence of IHP, showing that the spin equilibrium of the ferric iron (section 3.1) has been influenced towards higher spin. Perutz et al. suggest an interpretation for the spectral changes and for the change in spin equilibrium. They attribute them to the iron atom being held further out of the plane of the porphyrin ring with consequent lengthening of the iron-nitrogen bonds when the subunits are in the deoxy quaternary structure in the presence of IHP, than when the subunits are in the oxy quaternary structure in the absence of IHP.

