\section*{6. A MODEL FOR CO-OPERATIVE AND HETEROTROPIC INTERACTIONS IN HAEMOGLOBIN}

Some of the results discussed in the previous sections, including the properties of the cyanomet hybrids (section 5.2) and the effect of organic phosphates on the cooperativity of haemoglobin (sections 4.2 .7 and 5.1.2), give a strong indication that the type of model that describes the nature of the intermediate structures for haemoglobin and explains how co-operativity arises is that proposed by Monod et al. (1965). The basic idea of their allosteric model is outlined below.

Monod et al. (1965) proposed the following explanation for the origin of homotropic and heterotropic interactions in multi-subunit proteins. The subunits can associate in two different quaternary structures which are in equilibrium with each other at all stages of ligation. These structures differ in their inter-subunits bonds, and the quaternary constraints produced by these bonds alter the conformation of the subunits so that in one quaternary state the affinity of the subunits for ligand is higher than in the other. In the absence of ligand, the low affinity structure, the $T$ state, is the more stable. Binding ligand to the protein necessarily shifts the equilibrium towards the high affinity structure, the $R$ state, resulting in an increased affinity for ligand as ligation proceeds. Symmetry is conserved in that all subunits within one quaternary structure have the same affinity for ligand, and the affinity of a subunit is not influenced directly by the state of ligation of its neighbouring subunits. This model predicts that modifications to the protein will influence co-operative interactions through their effect on the affinities of the $R$ and $T$ states and on the equilibrium between the two quaternary structures. In particular, molecules that bind more strongly to one or other form will affect the allosteric equilibrium and such molecules are known as allosteric effectors. A property of the allosteric model, shown by Rubin and Changeux (1966), is that as the equilibrium between $R$ and $T$ in the absence of ligand is altered, either by changing the concentration of an allosteric effector, or by modification to the protein, the cooperativity as measured by $n$ is altered. The maximum co-operativity is obtained when the equilibrium is as far towards $T$ in unliganded haemoglobin as it is towards $R$ in fully liganded haemoglobin. If the equilibrium is either very far towards $T$ or towards $R$, there is no quaternary change on ligation and no co-operativity.

The allosteric model for haemoglobin. Monod et al. showed that their model was capable of accounting for the sigmoid oxygen equilibrium curve of haemoglobin, and it explains naturally the absence of co-operativity when there is no quaternary structure change. The necessity of the quaternary structure change for co-operativity in haemoglobin is well established (Perutz, 1970). All co-operative haemoglobins that have been investigated take up both the normal deoxy and the normal oxy quaternary structure, even though abnormal haemoglobins may have changes in detailed structure
at the contacts between subunits. In contrast, some non-cooperative haemoglobins, such as the high affinity haemoglobins discussed in section 5.1, have been shown not to change quaternary structure on oxygenation.

In principle the allosteric model can account for the heterotropic interactions of haemoglobin and the properties of abnormal haemoglobins by changes either in the intrinsic affinities for oxygen of the $R$ and $T$ states, or in the allosteric equilibrium between the $\mathbf{R}$ and $T$ forms. The allosteric model provides a framework in which many different phenomena in haemoglobin can be accounted for by the variation of a few parameters which are simply related to structural features in liganded and unliganded haemoglobin (Perutz, 1970).

The kinetic properties of the cyanomet hybrids show that two conformations of the hybrids, with different ligand binding properties exist together in solution in proportions that can be influenced by the presence of DPG and IHP. This has a simple interpretation in the allosteric model, with DPG and IHP as allosteric effectors (Ogawa and Shulman, 1971, 1972) although the equilibrium between the $R$ and $T$ forms in this case is slow (Cassoly and Gibson, 1972). The other experimental results on the properties of haemoglobin in the presence and absence of DPG and IHP also indicate that the mechanism proposed in the allosteric model contributes to the functional properties of haemoglobin, with DPG and IHP as allosteric effectors (Perutz, 1972; Perutz et al., 1974a, b, c).

The structural basis of the allosteric model for haemoglobin has been discussed by Perutz (1970). The model proposes the existence of an equilibrium between two quaternary structures at all stages of ligation. The structural information available for haemoglobin suggests that this is likely, with the two structures being those observed in fully liganded and unliganded haemoglobin. The tertiary structures of the subunits in the oxy and deoxy forms are sufficiently similar for the oxy subunits to associate in the deoxy quaternary structure, and for the deoxy subunits to associate in the oxy quaternary structure to a small extent. Indeed for modified haemoglobins this has been observed by X-ray techniques. The fact that all the mutant and modified haemoglobins so far studied by X-ray methods have been found to crystallize in one or other of the two normal quaternary structures is a strong indication that these two arrangements of subunits are especially stable, and that other quaternary structures are much less stable. ${ }^{3}$ Perutz $(1970,1972)$ and Perutz et al. $(1974 \mathrm{a}, \mathrm{b}, \mathrm{c})$ have discussed the stereochemical basis of co-operativity in the framework of the allosteric model. In section 7 there will be a detailed discussion of the incorporation of structural and other information into the allosteric model.

The possible role of direct interaction between subunits must be considered. An alternative model that could account for co-operative interactions in a multi-subunit protein like haemoglobin is the model developed by Koshland et al. (1966), elaborating an earlier model of Pauling (1935). In this type of model, the sequential model, the protein starts in a conformation that has low affinity for the first ligand. Binding ligand to one subunit of the protein produces conformation changes which directly influence the ligand binding properties of neighbouring subunits so that their affinities are either increased or decreased. Binding ligand to successive binding sites produces further conformation changes so that the protein is in a high affinity conformation for binding the last ligand. For haemoglobin the change in quaternary structure would be linked to the conformation changes that produce increasing affinity in such a way that the phenomena of co-operativity and the quaternary structure change always occurred together. This type of model is very general, and predicts the possibility of both co-operative and anti-cooperative behaviour. The equations for ligand binding in special cases where the direct interactions between subunits have particular geometries, for example the square and tetrahedral models, have been developed. A purely sequential model is capable of describing the sigmoid oxygen equilibrium curve of haemoglobin. It has the flexibility to describe the oxygen equilibrium in various conditions by adjusting its parameters, but these parameters are not easily related to structural features of the molecule. Such a model lacks the ability to account for many
properties of haemoglobin in a unified way, which is the great advantage of the allosteric model.

Direct interaction between subunits, along the lines of a sequential model, can be inqorporated into the allosteric model if it proves necessary to account for some properties of haemoglobin. An extension of this kind has been formulated by Szabo and Karplus (1975a). At present it seems that the simple allosteric model, with no interaction between subunits within the same quaternary structure but allowing for the difference between $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains, combined with the understanding of its parameters provided by structural evidence can give a qualitative explanation of many features of co-operative and heterotropic interactions in haemoglobin. Many authors have interpreted experimental results in terms of this model and their results will be discussed in section 7.

\section*{7. THE ALLOSTERIC THEORY OF LIGAND BINDING TO HAEMOGLOBIN}

This section will outline the development of the allosteric model for haemoglobin and show how it provides a unified way of describing and understanding many different aspects of haemoglobin function.

\subsection*{7.1. The Two Quaternary Structures and the Origin of Co-operativity}

Using the notation of Monod et al. (MWC), (1965), $\boldsymbol{R}$ denotes the relaxed or high affinity quaternary structure and $T$ denotes the tense or low affinity quaternary structure. Binding four oxygen molecules to haemoglobin is represented by the equilibrium diagram,
