Experimental results that appear inconsistent with the view that the $R$ structure is associated with an electronic absorption spectrum like free chains have been reported by Banerjee and Cassoly (1969a). The association of free met subunits into the tetramer altered the absorption spectrum of the $\beta$-subunits. Perutz et al. (1974c) suggest that this result is caused by a slight denaturation of the subunits in the free $\beta_{4}$-tetramer which is removed on their association into the haemoglobin tetramer.

The $T$ structure has intersubunit contacts that constrain the subunits to have lower oxygen affinity than free subunits. This lowered affinity is associated with the position of the iron atom further out of the plane of the porphyrin ring in a subunit in the $T$ state than in a free subunit (section 3.6). The iron-nitrogen bonds are longer and give rise to a characteristic absorption spectrum that differs from that of free chains (Perutz et al., 1974c). In the $\beta$-chains, the low affinity is also associated with the small size of the haem ligand pocket which has to widen to accommodate the ligand. The stability of $T_{0}$ is contributed to by the polar contacts within and between subunits involving the C -terminal residues of both $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains (section 3.4, Table 7).

