haemoglobin the residues Arg $141 \alpha$ and Tyr $140 \alpha$ are delocalized (see section 3.3). In deoxy BME Hb both these residues are more localized, with Tyr $140 \alpha$ stabilized in a pocket between the F and H helices. This change in conformation must be related to the different position of the iron atom (not seen at the resolution of the electron density map) and the absence of ligand in the haem pocket. There is also a noticeable change in tilt of the haem group relative to the protein part of a subunit which corresponds to the change seen in erythrocruorin (section 3.2) and between deoxy and met subunits in normal haemoglobin. The $\beta$-haems lose their ligand more easily than the $\alpha$-chains suggesting that they are less easily oxidized, in agreement with the relative oxidationreduction potentials of free $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits to which the $R$ state is believed to be similar. Also because the $R$ state affinity is like that of free subunits, the stability of the liganded $R$ state relative to free liganded subunits is almost the same as the stability of the unliganded $R$ state relative to free deoxy subunits. So structural indications of instability at the contacts between subunits in the met versus deoxy BME map are not expected if this abnormal haemoglobin is a good model for the $R$ state. In this connection it should be noticed that the affinity of BME Hb (Table 15) is somewhat lower than that expected for the normal $R$ state, that human deoxy BME Hb crystallizes in the deoxyquaternary structure although horse deoxy BME Hb crystallizes in $R$, and that deoxy BME Hb in the presence of phosphate has a normal deoxyhaemoglobin absorption spectrum rather than the spectrum of free subunits (Simon, S.R., unpublished).

Tertiary structure changes induced by ligation of subunits in the $T$ state were inferred from those seen when normal deoxy haemoglobin was oxidized in crystals containing acrylamide when the quaternary structure change did not occur (Anderson, 1973). When ligand binds to a haem group in the $T$ state, tertiary structure changes accompanying the changed radius of the iron atom must destabilize some of the inter-subunit contacts that hold the iron atom $0.2 / 0.3 \AA$ further out of the plane of the porphyrin ring in the $T$ state than in a free deoxy subunit. Ligation of successive subunits will increase the destabilization of the inter-subunit contacts and at some stage in ligation the $R$ quaternary structure becomes more stable than the $T$.

From Anderson's results there are indications of where the instability of the contacts occurs when the iron atom changes its position from that of the high spin ferrous state of deoxyhaemoglobin to that of the high spin ferric state of aquomet haemoglobin at pH 6.5. The iron atom was closer to the plane of the porphyrin ring in the met form, the haem pocket was wider and the haem group had the same orientation in the pocket as in liganded BME Hb and normal haemoglobin. The different position of the iron atom was associated with the loosening of several hydrogen bonds within and between subunits at the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ interface, but the C -terminal salt bridges of both the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains appeared intact and His $146 \beta$ remained salt bridged to Asp $94 \beta$. The ionizing groups responsible for some of the normal oxidation Bohr effect were therefore unperturbed. The electron density in the map was less for the $\beta$-haem ligand than for the $\alpha$-haem ligand, showing that oxidation was not complete and that the $\alpha$-chains were more easily oxidized than the $\beta$-chains. This latter result is consistent with the results of MacQuarrie and Gibson (1971) (see section 4.1.4) and with the suggestion of Perutz (1970) that the $\beta$-haems in deoxyhaemoglobin would combine less easily than the $\alpha$-chains with a ligand because of the smaller size of the $\beta$-haems pocket.

Ligation in the $T$ state with different ligands is expected to destabilize the $T$ structure to different extents. As discussed in section 3.1, the radius of the iron atom depends on its valency and spin state. The unstrained position of the iron atom when a free subunit is combined with a ligand for which the iron atom is in a low spin ferrous or ferric state is in the plane of the porphyrin ring. For a ligand like the water molecule at low pH , the iron atom is in a high spin ferric state and its unstrained position is $0.4 \AA$ out of the plane. Thus tertiary structure changes following ligation of subunits would be expected to be larger for oxygenation than for oxidation at pH 6.5 , and the destabilization of the $T$ structure would be greater (Szabo and Karplus, 1972; Hopfield, 1973; Perutz et al., 1974b). For an oxidized haem at high pH , when the water molecule is ionized, the spin of the ferric iron is less, due to the existence of an equilibrium between the high and low
spin states (Table 4, section 3.1). The radius of the iron atom, the unstrained position of the iron atom in a free subunit, the tertiary structure changes accompanying ligation and the destabilization of the $T$ state will all therefore be intermediate between the corresponding properties for oxygenated haemoglobin and haemoglobin oxidized at low pH .

Both the structural comparisons described in preceding paragraphs were of the aquomet and the deoxy forms. The tertiary structures of the oxy and deoxy forms are expected to differ more. In particular, the C-terminal salt bridges may be broken and the ionizing groups contributing to the Bohr effect may be perturbed. The latter result is expected from the experimental results on linearity of proton release with carbon monoxide uptake described in section 4.1.3. The lag in the fraction of protons released as a function of percentage oxidation at pH 6.5 (see section 4.1.4) is consistent with the crystallographic results that in this case some of the Bohr groups are not perturbed in the $T$ state.

Since ligation in the $R$ state does not introduce instability in the intersubunit contacts as there are almost no constraints in $R$, oxidation and oxygenation are as easy in the $R$ state as in free chains. In the $T$ state, however, oxygenation is more difficult relative to oxygenation of free chains than is oxidation relative to oxidation of free chains because of the larger movement required of the iron atom. Hopfield (1973) has estimated from a linear theory of the energy distribution in haemoglobin that the difference between the free energy of ligand binding in the $T$ state and that of binding to free chains is only 2.1 kcal per haem in the case of oxidation at low pH , compared to about 3.6 kcal per haem for oxygenation. These free energy differences correspond to $c$ being about 0.03 for oxidation at low pH , and 0.003 for oxygenation. $c$ for oxidation at high pH will have some intermediate value. Another method of estimating relative $c$ values for different ligands will be discussed in section 7.3.

\subsection*{7.2. The Allosteric Model with Four Equivalent Subunits}

Many of the features generally used to describe oxygen equilibrium curves can be given simple algebraic expressions in terms of the allosteric model parameters.

The median ligand activity is easily obtained from its definition
$$p_{m}^{4}=\frac{1}{A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime} A_{3}^{\prime} A_{4}^{\prime}} \quad(\text { section 2.2) }$$

Substituting for the Adair constants from (7.1)
$$\begin{gathered}
p_{m}^{4}=K_{R}^{4}\left(\frac{1+L}{1+L c^{4}}\right) \\
\text { or } \log p_{m}=\log K_{R}+\frac{1}{4} \log \left(\frac{1+L}{1+L c^{4}}\right) .
\end{gathered}$$

The difference in free energy of binding the first and last ligand $\Delta F_{I}$ can be obtained by substituting the values of $A_{1}^{\prime}$ and $A_{4}^{\prime}$ from (7.1) into its definition (eq. (2.12))
$$\Delta F_{I}=-\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{1}^{\prime}+\mathrm{RT} \ln A_{4}^{\prime}=\mathrm{RT} \ln \frac{\left(1+L c^{4}\right)}{\left(1+L C^{3}\right)} \frac{(1+L)}{(1+L c)} .$$

The value of $p_{50}$ is given by the expression
$$L=\frac{\left(\gamma_{50}-1\right)\left(1+\gamma_{50}\right)^{3}}{\left(1-\gamma_{50} c\right)\left(1+\gamma_{50} c\right)^{3}}$$
where $y_{50}=p_{50} / K_{R}$. This can be shown by substituting the expressions for the Adair constants (7.1) in the definition of $p_{50}$ given in section 2.3 (eq. (2.13)).

The slope of the Hill plot at $p_{50}$ is
$$n=1+\frac{3\left(1-c \gamma_{50}\right)\left(\gamma_{50}-1\right)}{\left(1+c \gamma_{50}\right)\left(\gamma_{50}+1\right)}$$

This can be shown from the definition of $n$ given in eq. (2.14) expressing ( $\bar{Y} / 1-\bar{Y}$ ) (eq. (2.11)) in terms of the allosteric model parameters. Bunn and Guidotti (1972) give this expression for $n$.

