\subsection*{7.3. The Allosteric Model of M Haemoglobins and Mixed-valency Hybrids}

The M haemoglobins and the mixed-valency hybrids, whose properties were described in section 5.2, have only two sites for oxygen ligand. The algebraic expressions for the parameters used to characterize the oxygen equilibrium curves are easily obtained by analogy with the results already given for the case of four binding sites.

The Adair constants become
$$\begin{aligned}
& A_{1}^{\prime}=\frac{1}{K_{R}}\left(\frac{L_{M} c+1}{L_{M}+1}\right), \\
& A_{2}^{\prime}=\frac{1}{K_{R}}\left(\frac{L_{M} c^{2}+1}{L_{M} c+1}\right)
\end{aligned}$$
where $L_{M}=[T] /[R]$ for the modified haemoglobin or hybrid with no oxygen bound and $c=K_{R} / K_{T}$ for the type of chain free to bind ligand.

The median ligand activity is given by
$$p_{m}^{2}=\frac{1}{A_{1}^{\prime} A_{2}^{\prime}} .$$

Substituting the values of the Adair constants from (7.11)
$$p_{m}^{2}=K_{R}^{2}\left(\frac{L_{M}+1}{L_{M} c^{2}+1}\right)$$
or
$$\log p_{m}=\log K_{R}+\frac{1}{2} \log \left(\frac{L_{M}+1}{L_{M} c^{2}+1}\right) .$$

The value of $p_{50}$ is always equal to the value of $p_{m}$ when there are only two binding sites which implies that the oxygen equilibrium curves are symmetrical (Wyman, 1967; Szabo and Karplus, 1975c).

The slope of the Hill plot at $p_{50}$ can easily be shown to be
$$n_{50}=\left[\frac{2}{1+\frac{L_{M} C+1}{\left[\left(L_{M} C^{2}+1\right)\left(L_{M}+1\right)\right]^{1 / 2}}}\right] .$$

The dependence of Hill plot parameters on the value of $L_{M}$. When $L_{M}$ is very small,
$$\begin{aligned}
p_{50}=p_{m} & \longrightarrow K_{R}, \\
n & \longrightarrow 1 .
\end{aligned}$$

When $L_{M}$ is very high, such that $L_{M} C^{2}$ is also high,
$$\begin{aligned}
p_{50}=p_{m} & \longrightarrow K_{T}, \\
n & \longrightarrow 1 .
\end{aligned}$$

When $L_{M} C=1$,
$$\begin{aligned}
p_{50} & =p_{m}=\left(K_{R} K_{T}\right)^{1 / 2} \\
n & =\frac{2}{1+\frac{2 \sqrt{c}}{(1+c)}} .
\end{aligned}$$

A plot of $n_{50}$ versus $\log L_{M}$ is a bell-shaped curve with maximum $n$ at the point $L_{M}=1 / c$, falling to 1 for large and small $L_{M}$. For $c=0.003$, which is the order of magnitude appropriate for haemoglobin, the maximum $n$ will be 1.8 . Figure 19 illustrates the variation of $\left(\log p_{50}-\log K_{R}\right)$ and the variation of $n$ with $\log L_{M}$ for $c=0.003$. As in the case of four binding sites, the slope of $\log p_{50}$ versus $\log L_{M}$ is constant over the middle range of $L_{M}$, the slope in this case being approximately $\frac{1}{2}$. In this range of $L_{M}$ the following approximate expression can be used to estimate values of $\log L_{M}$ :
