\subsection*{7.4 The Kinetics of Ligand Binding in the Allosteric Model}

There is no unique kinetic scheme that corresponds to the allosteric model of equilibrium binding properties, and the following diagram illustrates the kinetic parameters involved:
$$\begin{aligned}
& T_{0}+4 \mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{T 1}}{\stackrel{k_{T 1}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} T_{1}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{T 2}}{\stackrel{k_{T 2}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} T_{2}+2 \mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{T 3}}{\stackrel{k_{T 3}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} T_{3}+\mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{T 4}}{\stackrel{k_{T 4}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} T_{4} \\
& q_{0}\left\|q_{0}^{\prime} \quad q_{1}\right\| q_{1}^{\prime} \quad q_{2}\left\|q_{2}^{\prime} \quad q_{3}\right\| q_{3}^{\prime} \quad q_{4} \| q_{4}^{\prime} \\
& R_{0}+4 \mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{R 1}}{\stackrel{k_{R 1}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} R_{1}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{R 2}}{\stackrel{k_{R 2}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} R_{2}+2 \mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{R 3}}{\stackrel{k_{R 3}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} R_{3}+\mathrm{O}_{2} \underset{k_{R 4}}{\stackrel{k_{R 4}^{\prime}}{\rightleftharpoons}} R_{4}
\end{aligned}$$

The ratio of the "off" to the "on" constant for each ligation step in one quaternary state equals the equilibrium constant for ligand binding in that state, for example
$$K_{R}=\frac{k_{R 1}}{k_{R 1}^{\prime}}=\frac{k_{R 2}}{k_{R 2}^{\prime}}=\frac{k_{R 3}}{k_{R 3}^{\prime}}=\frac{k_{R 4}}{k_{R 4}^{\prime}} .$$

In general, although the equilibrium constant for each quaternary structure is independent of ligation step, the kinetic constants could alter at each step, provided both alter by the same factor. This would correspond to interaction between the subunits within one quaternary structure, not apparent in the equilibrium constant but altering the rate constants, and emphasizes the fact that kinetic constants are more closely related to mechanism than are equilibrium constants.

Hopfield et al. (1971) have discussed the kinetic scheme in which the kinetic constants as well as the equilibrium constants are independent of the state of ligation of other subunits within $R$ and $T$, so that
$$K_{R}=\frac{k_{R}}{k_{R}^{\prime}} \quad \text { and } \quad K_{T}=\frac{k_{T}}{k_{T}^{\prime}} .$$

The rate constants for the conformational transitions from $T$ to $R$ must satisfy the relationships $q_{i} / q_{i}^{\prime}=L c^{i}$ where $i$ is the number of ligands bound. Hopfield et al. set up the equations for the rate constants for binding successive ligands on the assumption that the conformational transitions between $T$ and $R$ were fast compared to the rate of ligand binding at all stages of ligation and treating the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains as equivalent. In these circumstances the successive rate constants for ligand uptake must increase, and, for example, it is not possible for the third step to be slower than the second step. If the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains are not equivalent or if $T$ to $R$ transitions are not fast compared to ligand binding at all stages, the situation is more complicated. Hopfield et al. (1971, 1972) have shown that their simple model can account for many features of the kinetics of ligand binding to haemoglobin, but evidence on the different kinetic properties of $\alpha$ and $\beta$-chains (Gray and Gibson, 1971b; MacQuarrie and Gibson, 1971; Olson and

Gibson, 1971 a,b, 1973 a,b; Gibson, 1973a), shows that a model must take these differences into account. It must also allow abnormal haemoglobins to have altered parameters (Hewitt and Gibson, 1973). Even allowing for $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains to have different constants, some kinetic properties of abnormal haemoglobins do not have an obvious interpretation in terms of the allosteric model (Moffat et al., 1973; Olson et al., 1972; Tan et al., 1973). Other experiments can be interpreted in terms of the model only if $T$ to $R$ transitions are slow (Cassoly et al., 1971; Cassoly and Gibson, 1972).

