\subsection*{7.6. The Interaction with Protons in the Allosteric Model}

The structural understanding of the difference in proton binding to deoxy and to fully liganded haemoglobin was discussed in section 4.1. All the intermediate structures formed during ligation may bind protons differently, implying that the five parameters of the allosteric model are pH dependent. The general equations for the allosteric model with pH -dependent parameters, and the structural and other evidence on proton binding to the intermediate structures will be discussed in this section.

In the following discussion $\mathrm{H}^{+}$denotes the hydrogen ion and $h$ the concentration of hydrogen ions.

If $\mathrm{H}^{+}$binds differently to liganded and unliganded subunits, then by analogy with the discussion of section 2.6.2, the following results hold. Let $\phi_{s 0}(h)$ be the binding polynomial for protons to an unliganded subunit and $\phi_{s 1}(h)$ that for the liganded subunits. These polynomials involve the ionization constants of the groups whose $\mathbf{p K}$ values are perturbed on ligation of the subunit. If $K$ is the oxygen dissociation constant for a subunit when the proton concentration is very low (i.e. high $\mathbf{p H}$ ) and if $\boldsymbol{K}_{h}$ is the value when the proton concentration is $h$
$$K_{h}=K \frac{\phi_{s 0}(h)}{\phi_{s_{1}}(h)}$$
and the amount of $\mathrm{H}^{+}$released when a subunit is ligated is $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{s}^{+}$in
$$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{s}^{+}=\frac{d \log \phi_{S 0}(h)}{d \log h}-\frac{d \log \phi_{S 1}(h)}{d \log h}$$
or
$$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{S}^{+}=\frac{d \log K_{h}}{d \log h}=-\frac{d \log K_{h}}{d \mathrm{pH}} .$$

Thus for $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits in the $R$ and $T$ states
$$\Delta H_{\mathrm{T} \alpha}^{+}=\frac{-d \log K_{\mathrm{T} \alpha}}{d \mathrm{pH}} ; \Delta H_{R \alpha}^{+}=\frac{-d \log K_{\mathrm{R} \alpha}}{d \mathrm{pH}}, \text { etc. }$$

If the subunit has only one binding site for protons $\phi_{S 0}(h)$ and $\phi_{S 1}(h)$ have the simple form
$$\phi_{S 0}(h)=\left(1+B_{S 0} h\right)=\left(1+\frac{h}{K_{S 0}}\right)=\left(1+10^{p^{\mathbf{p}} \mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{s 0}}-\mathbf{p H}}\right)$$
where $\mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{s o}}=10^{-p K_{\mathbf{s o}}}$ is the ionization constant of the proton binding site in a deoxy subunit.

Similarly,
$$\phi_{S 1}(h)=\left(1-10^{p K_{s 1}-\mathrm{pH}}\right)$$
and
$$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{s}^{+}=\frac{10^{\mathrm{p} K_{s o}}}{1+10^{\mathrm{p} K_{s o}-\mathrm{pH}}}-\frac{10^{\mathrm{p} K_{s 1}}}{1+10^{\mathrm{pK} K_{s 1}-\mathrm{pH}}} .$$

In general there may be more than one proton binding site per subunit whose ionization constant changes on ligation of the subunit, and $\phi_{s 0}(h)$ and $\phi_{s 1}(h)$ are longer polynomials. If the proton binding sites within a subunit are independent $\phi_{s o}(h)$ can be written as a product of terms (see section 2.6.2)
and
$$\Delta \mathbf{H}_{s}^{+}=\sum_{i=1}^{q} \Delta \mathbf{H}_{3 i}^{+}$$

A complete formulation of the allosteric model requires specification of $\phi_{s o}(h)$ and $\phi_{s_{1}}(h)$ for the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in the $R$ and $T$ states in terms of the $\mathbf{p} K$ changes of identified Bohr groups. It is possible that a particular Bohr group has a different $\mathbf{p K}$ in intermediate states from the pK it has in either deoxy-or oxyhaemoglobin.

If $\mathrm{H}^{+}$binds differently to the $R$ and $T$ states, and if $\phi_{T}(h)$ and $\phi_{R}(h)$ are the binding polynomials for the $T$ and $R$ states respectively, then
$$L_{h}=L \frac{\phi_{T}(h)}{\phi_{R}(h)}$$
and
$$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Q}}^{+}=\frac{d \log L_{h}}{d \log h}=-\frac{d \log L_{h}}{d \mathrm{pH}}$$
where $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Q}}^{+}$is the number of protons released when the quaternary structure changes irrespective of the state of ligation of the subunits.

If there are several binding sites for protons in $R$ and $T$ which from structural considerations are not expected to interact directly with each other,
$$\phi_{T}(h)=\left(1+\frac{h}{\mathbf{K}_{T 1}}\right)\left(1+\frac{h}{\mathbf{K}_{T 2}}\right) \cdots\left(1+\frac{h}{\mathbf{K}_{T q}}\right)$$
and
$$\phi_{R}(h)=\left(1+\frac{h}{\mathbf{K}_{R 1}}\right)\left(1+\frac{h}{\mathbf{K}_{R 2}}\right) \cdots\left(1+\frac{h}{\mathbf{K}_{R q}}\right)$$
where $\mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{T} 1}, \mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{R} 1}$, etc., denote the ionization constants of the Bohr groups. Then
$$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Q}}^{+}=\sum_{i=1}^{q} \frac{-d \log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{\mathrm{TI}}}\right)}{d \mathrm{pH}}+\frac{d \log \left(1+\frac{d}{\mathrm{~K}_{\mathrm{Ri}}}\right)}{d \mathrm{pH}} .$$

Also,
$$\log L_{h}=\log L+\sum_{i=i}^{q}\left[\log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{\mathrm{TI}}}\right)-\log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{\mathrm{RI}}}\right)\right]$$
which expresses the pH dependence of the parameter $L_{n}$. Again the complete formulation of the model requires specification of identified Bohr groups whose $\mathbf{p} \boldsymbol{K}$ 's change between $R$ and $T$.

The expression for the total release of protons on ligation is
$$\frac{\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+}}{4}=-\frac{d \log p_{m}}{d \mathrm{pH}} \quad(\text { see eq. (4.2)) }$$

From eq. (7.17),
$$\log p_{m}=\frac{1}{2} \log K_{R \alpha}+\frac{1}{2} \log K_{R \beta}+\frac{1}{4} \log \frac{(L+1)}{\left(L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}+1\right)} .$$

Differentiating the above equation,
$$\begin{aligned}
\frac{d \log p_{m}}{d \mathrm{pH}}= & \frac{1}{2\left(1+L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)}\left(\frac{d \log K_{\mathrm{R} \alpha}}{d \mathrm{pH}}+\frac{d \log K_{\mathrm{R} \beta}}{d \mathrm{pH}}\right) \\
& +\frac{L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}}{2\left(1+L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)}\left(\frac{d \log K_{\mathrm{r} \alpha}}{d \mathrm{pH}}+\frac{d \log K_{\mathrm{r} \beta}}{d \mathrm{pH}}\right) \\
& +\frac{1}{4} \frac{L\left(1-c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)}{(L+1)\left(1+L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)} \times \frac{d \log L}{d \mathrm{pH}}
\end{aligned}$$
or substituting from eqs. (7.19) and (7.20)
$$\begin{gathered}
\frac{\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+}}{4}=\frac{1}{2\left(1+L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)}\left(\Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \alpha}^{+}+\Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \beta}^{+}\right)+\frac{L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}}{2\left(1+L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)}\left(\Delta \mathrm{H}_{T \alpha}^{+}+\Delta \mathrm{H}_{T \beta}^{+}\right) \\
+\frac{1}{4} \frac{L\left(1-c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)}{(L+1)\left(1+L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2}\right)} \Delta \mathrm{H}_{Q}^{+}
\end{gathered}$$

So the total release of bound protons is made up of the contributions from five possible terms.

Interaction between binding sites for protons. The terms $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{Q}^{+}, \Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \alpha}^{+}$, etc., will be the sums of contributions from independent binding sites if there is no interaction between sites within subunits or within quaternary structures, which is reasonable if the ionizing groups are far apart. In general $\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+} / 4$, given by eq. (7.23), reflects the interaction between the binding sites that occurs because of the quaternary structure change. In some simple cases the binding sites are actually or effectively independent of each other. Firstly, if the quaternary structure does not change from either $R$ or $T$ with change in ligation state, $\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+} / 4$ involves only sums of independent terms, which is also the case if proton binding is entirely linked to tertiary structure changes so that $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Q}}^{+}=0$, with $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{R} \alpha}^{+}=\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{T} \alpha}^{+}$and $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{R} \beta}^{+}=\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{T} \beta}^{+}$. Secondly, if $L \geqslant 1$ and $L c_{\alpha}^{2} c_{\beta}^{2} \ll 1$, corresponding to the quaternary structure changing completely from $T$ to $R$ during oxygenation, $\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+} / 4$ can be approximated by
$$\frac{\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+}}{4}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{R} \alpha}^{+}+\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{R} \beta}^{+}\right)+\frac{1}{4} \Delta \mathrm{H}_{Q}^{+}$$
which is again a sum of independent contributions. This condition on $L$ applies to normal haemoglobin so that protons bind to effectively independent sites, even if proton binding is not independent of the quaternary structure change. For values of $L$ not satisfying the above condition, the interaction between binding sites due to any quaternary linkage of proton binding will be apparent.

The release of protons at each stage of ligation will be an exactly linear function of the fractional saturation with ligand, $\bar{Y}$, only if
$$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \alpha}^{+}=\Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \beta}^{+}=\Delta \mathrm{H}_{T \alpha}^{+}=\Delta \mathrm{H}_{T \beta}^{+} \text {and } \Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Q}}^{+}=0$$

Otherwise there will be a non-linear relationship. In a co-operative haemoglobin, however, the deviation from linearity will not be very great even if the change in number of bound protons is entirely linked to the quaternary structure change. For example, in Fig. 17 the change in fraction of molecules in the $R$ and $T$ structures is shown as a function of $\bar{Y}$ for two cases where the co-operativity is high and the deviation of the fraction in $R$ from being a linear function of the fraction $\bar{Y}$ is quite small. In practice for the oxygenation of normal haemoglobin the release of protons is apparently linear with ligand saturation although it is known from other considerations that it cannot be strictly so. For oxidation at pH 6.5 the release of protons lags behind ligand saturation showing that some protons in this case must be released when the quaternary structure changes.

Experimental evidence relating to the stage at which various Bohr groups contribute their protons. Proton release in carbon monoxide and oxygen binding. As discussed in section 4.1.3, equilibrium results on oxygen and carbon monoxide binding to haemoglobin at different pH values and kinetic measurements of proton release on uptake of these ligands indicate that at alkaline pH proton release is proportional to the amount of ligand bound in the early stages of ligation. This strict proportionality does not apply for the last binding step and the equilibrium and kinetic results give a less clear indication of how much proton release is associated with this step. Proportionality in the early stages, when normal haemoglobin is in the $T$ state, implies that all the alkaline Bohr groups contribute to the pH dependence of either $\boldsymbol{K}_{\boldsymbol{T \alpha}}$ or $\boldsymbol{K}_{\boldsymbol{T \beta}}$. Since proton release comes from the ionizing groups whose $\mathbf{p} \boldsymbol{K}$ 's are raised as a result of the groups being involved in salt bridges, the latter must be broken on oxygenation in the $T$ state. This conclusion was incorporated
into the proposal of Perutz (1970). Since $A_{4}^{\prime}$ depends very little on pH , tertiary structure changes in $R$ cannot release many protons, i.e. $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \alpha}^{+}$and $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{R \beta}^{+}$are smaller than $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{T}_{\alpha}}^{+}$ and $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{T} \beta}^{+}$. This implies that $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{Q}}^{+}$, the number of protons that would be released on the quaternary structure change, whatever the state of ligation of the subunits, is significant and consequently L is pH dependent. Since $K_{R \alpha}$ and $K_{R \beta}$ are less pH dependent than $K_{T \alpha}$ and $\boldsymbol{K}_{\boldsymbol{T} \boldsymbol{\beta}}, \boldsymbol{c}_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}$ and $\boldsymbol{c}_{\beta}$ are also pH dependent.

The dependence of $n$ on pH . Bunn and Guidotti (1972) investigated the pH dependence of $n$ and $\log p_{s o}$ for oxygenation in various salt concentrations. They found that at low ionic strength when the affinity of haemoglobin is quite high, $n$ increases slightly with decreasing pH. At high ionic strength, in the presence of DPG and IHP when the oxygen affinity is lower, $n$ increases slightly with increasing pH . This type of variation of $n$ is qualitatively to be expected from the allosteric model if $L$ is to some extent pH dependent (see Fig. 16). The small degree of variation of $n$ with pH suggests that proton release is not entirely linked to the quaternary structure change, and is consistent with $c_{\alpha}$ and $c_{\beta}$ being pH dependent, as concluded above. The pH dependent $n$ values of cat haemoglobin and of Hb Milwaukee are consistent with a pH dependent value of $L$ (Hamilton and Edelstein, 1972) and many equilibrium properties of carp haemoglobin, which shows a very large variation in properties with pH , have been accounted for quite successfully with a pH -dependent $L$ in the allosteric model (Tan et al., 1973; Tan and Noble, 1973). Also the pH dependent $n$ values of $\operatorname{des}(\operatorname{Arg})$ and Hb Chesapeake are explained by the low values of $L$ for these haemoglobins (see Fig. 21) which makes their $n$ values very sensitive to small changes of $L$ with pH .

Proton release from $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in $n$-BIC binding. In contrast to the proportionality of proton release with carbon monoxide uptake, there is a lag in proton release with uptake of the ligand n-BIC (see section 4.1.3). Olson and Gibson (1973a) estimate that $20 \%$ of the proton release associated with n-BIC binding occurs with the fast phase of ligand binding, which has been shown to correspond to ligation of the $\beta$-chains. In the allosteric model this implies that ligation of the $\beta$-chains in the $T$ state with n -BIC releases protons, presumably from perturbation of the His $146 \beta$-Asp $94 \beta$ salt bridge. The remaining protons released with the slower phase include all protons released from the $\alpha$-chains and with the quaternary structure change. At the pH of the experiment ( pH 7.0 ) the His $146 \beta$-Asp $94 \beta$ salt bridge has been shown to contribute about $30 \%$ of the total protons released on oxygenation (Kilmartin et al., 1973). Olson and Gibson's finding of $20 \%$ of the protons associated with the $\beta$-chains can be taken to indicate that with the ligand n-BIC the tertiary structure changes induced by ligation of the $\beta$-chains only perturb the His $146 \beta$-Asp $94 \beta$ salt bridge and no other ionizing groups. The unidentified Bohr group must therefore release its protons on ligation of the $\alpha$-chains or when the quaternary structure changes. If the tertiary structure changes induced by binding n-BIC are the same as those for binding carbon monoxide, for which case there is no lag in proton release, the unidentified ionizing groups must release protons on ligation of the $\alpha$-chains in the $T$ state.

The binding of protons to partially oxidized haemoglobin. As discussed in section 4.1.4, in the oxidation-reduction equilibrium of haemoglobin, $n$ varies with pH and the release of protons is non-linear with fractional oxidation. At pH 6.5 there is a clear lag in release of protons with percentage oxidation whereas at high pH the lag is much less. In section 7.1 it was discussed that at pH 6.5 the salt bridges responsible for part of the oxidation Bohr effect are not perturbed when oxidation occurs in the $T$ state. The salt bridge between His $146 \beta$ and Asp $94 \beta$ and the environment of the $\alpha$-amino group of the $\alpha$-chains were not altered. As mentioned in section 4.2.7, Kilmartin (1973) has shown that when the quaternary structure change on oxidation is prevented by the presence of IHP, half the normal number of protons are released on oxidation, which must be the contribution of the unidentified Bohr groups since the two identified Bohr groups do not contribute in the T state. At pH 6.5 , therefore, the two identified Bohr groups do not contribute to $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{T_{\alpha}}^{+}$and $\Delta \mathrm{H}_{T \beta}^{+}$whereas the other group does, and protons will be released from the identified Bohr groups only on the quaternary structure change. The release of protons from met $\beta$ subunits when the quaternary structure
changes is observed in Hb Milwaukee, for which the number of protons released per tetramer on oxygenation is almost equal to that for normal haemoglobin although the $\beta$-chains stay in the met form.

Comparison of oxidation and oxygenation. The decrease in $n$ with decreasing pH for the oxidation of haemoglobin compared to the almost constant $n$ for oxygenation can be explained by the allosteric model as a consequence of $L$ being pH dependent and $c$ for oxidation being greater than $c$ for oxygenation (Hopfield, 1973; Perutz et al., 1974c; Szabo and Karplus, 1975c). This latter difference is to be expected as explained in section 7.1.

The qualitative explanation of the difference in dependence of $n$ on pH for oxidation and oxygenation can be seen from Fig. 18. The parameter $c$ for oxygenation depends on pH because the breaking of pH -dependent salt bridges is linked to tertiary structure changes on ligation in $T$. $c$ for oxidation is different at pH 6.5 and pH 8.0 because in the first case the ferric iron atom has high spin and in the second case it has lower spin. If $c$ for oxygenation at pH 6.5 gives the curve (1) and at pH 8.0 gives the curve (3) then, since $L$ is pH dependent varying between about $10^{6}$ and $10^{4}, n$ for oxygenation will be fairly constant at about 3 , as shown by the open circles marked on the curves. If curve (5) corresponds to oxidation at pH 6.5 and curve (4) to oxidation at pH 8.0 where $c$ is smaller, then $n$ will vary from 1.2 to 2.6 for the same change in $L$. This is qualitatively the variation of $n$ seen in oxidation as pH is changed. The free $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains of haemoglobin are known to differ more in their oxidation-reduction potentials than in their oxygen affinities, by a factor of about 10 as opposed to a factor of 2 , and these differences are probably retained in the tetramer. Figure 20 illustrated the decrease in $n$ produced by a difference in affinity of a factor of 10 between the subunits. This effect will also contribute to the lower $n$ values in oxidation than in oxygenation.

The effect of IHP on the Bohr effects of abnormal haemoglobins. Kilmartin et al. (1975) have studied the Bohr effects of modified haemoglobins in the presence and absence of IHP. Table 18 gave the number of protons released by these abnormal haemoglobins on oxygenation at pH 7.4 , expressed as a percentage of the number of protons released by HbA . The negligible Bohr effect of des(Arg.Tyr) in the absence of phosphates and its restoration to $75 \%$ in the presence of IHP imply that the His $146 \beta$-Asp $94 \beta$ salt bridge cannot form in deoxy $\beta$-subunits in the $R$ state whereas it does in the $T$ state. This is consistent with the results of an X-ray study of an abnormal deoxyhaemoglobin in the $R$ state, horse des(Arg), in which the His $146 \beta$-Asp $94 \beta$ salt bridge was seen to be broken (Perutz, unpublished). The negligible Bohr effect of NES des(Arg) in the absence of phosphates and its restoration to $60 \%$ in the presence of IHP implies that the $\alpha$-amino group of the $\alpha$-chains and some other ionizing group can only contribute to the Bohr effect if the deoxyhaemoglobin is in the $T$ state.

Table 18 shows that the Bohr effect of des(Arg) and Hb Kempsey are increased from about 40 to $100 \%$ of normal by the addition of IHP. Also the Bohr effect of des(His.Tyr) is increased by the addition of IHP. No known Bohr group is expected to be directly perturbed either in Hb Kempsey or in $\operatorname{des}(\mathrm{Arg})$, and $\operatorname{des}(\mathrm{His} . \mathrm{Tyr})$ would have a $50 \%$ Bohr effect if all ionizing groups except His $146 \beta$ were contributing as normal. The probable explanation of the reduced but not negligible Bohr effects for these three haemoglobins in the absence of IHP is that $L$ is small. Equation (7.23) shows that the exact number of protons released is extremely sensitive to the value of $L$ when $L$ is small. For example, if $L=1,50 \%$ of the quaternary linked Bohr will be present and if $L=2,66 \%$. When $L$ is increased to a large value by the addition of IHP, $\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+}$would be restored to the normal value.

